6-800.pdf online]\n* Gerwarth, Robert, and Erez Manela, eds. ''Empires at War: 1911-1923'' (2014), 12 very wide-ranging essays by scholars. [https://www.amazon.com/Empires-War-1911-1923-Greater-dp-0198702515/dp/0198702515/  excerpt]\n* Goldsworthy, Adrian, and John Keegan. ''Roman Warfare'' (2000)\n* Horne, John, ed. ''A Companion to World War I'' (2012)\n* Keegan, John. ''A History of Warfare'' (1994)\n* Kennedy, Paul. ''The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers'' (1989)\n* Paret, Peter, ed. ''Makers of Modern Strategy'' (1986), ideas of warfare\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1093/actrade/9780199590964.001.0001|title=The Napoleonic Wars|year=2013|last1=Rapport|first1=Mike|isbn=9780199590964}}\n* [[David Stevenson (historian)|Stevenson, David]]. ''Cataclysm: The First World War As Political Tragedy'' (2004) major reinterpretation, 560pp\n* [[Hew Strachan|Strachan, Hew]]. ''The First World War: Volume I: To Arms'' (2004): a major scholarly synthesis. Thorough coverage of 1914-16; 1245pp\n* {{Cite book|last=Weinberg|first=Gerhard L. |year=2005|title=A World at Arms: A Global History of World War II|edition=2nd|ref=harv}}; comprehensive overview with emphasis on diplomacy\n* Winter, J. M. ''The Experience of World War I'' (2nd ed 2005), topical essays;\n* Zeiler, Thomas W. and Daniel M. DuBois, eds. ''A Companion to World War II'' (2 vol 2013), 1030 pp; comprehensive overview by scholars\n\n===Women and gender===\n* Anderson, Bonnie S. and Judith P. Zinsser. ''A History of Their Own: Women in Europe from Prehistory to the Present'' (2nd ed 2000)\n* Bridenthal, Renate, et al. eds. ''Becoming Visible: Women in European History'' (3rd ed. 1997), 608 pp; essays by scholars\n* Frey, Linda, Marsha Frey, Joanne Schneider. ''Women in Western European History: A Select Chronological, Geographical, and Topical Bibliography'' (1982) [https://www.questia.com/library/70061929/women-in-western-european-history-a-select-chronological online]\n* Hufton, Olwen. ''The Prospect Before Her: A History of Women in Western Europe, 1500-1800'' (1996)\n* {{cite book|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511997075|title=Sexuality in Europe|year=2011|last1=Herzog|first1=Dagmar|isbn=9780511997075}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1353/jowh.0.0131|title=Surveying European Women's History since the Millenium: A Comparative Review|journal=Journal of Women's History|volume=22|pages=154\u2013177|year=2010|last1=Karen Offen}}\n* {{cite book|doi=10.5040/9781350001688|title=Gender, Sex and the Shaping of Modern Europe|year=2016|last1=Sanborn|first1=Joshua A.|last2=Timm|first2=Annette F.|isbn=9781350001688}}\n* {{cite book|doi=10.1017/9781108683524|title=Women and Gender in Early Modern Europe|year=2019|last1=Wiesner-Hanks|first1=Merry E.|isbn=9781108683524|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/85c1c799aeead8f9e03d67141b6f287858452bcc}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|History of Europe}}\n{{Commons|Atlas of European history}}\n{{Commons|Old maps of Europe}}\n{{Wikibooks|European History}}\n{{Wikiversity|European History}}\n{{Wikivoyage|European history|European history|travel information}}\n* [http://hsozkult.geschichte.hu-berlin.de/eurhistxx.asp EurhistXX: The Network for the Contemporary History of Europe], edited in English from Berlin\n* [http://bookshop.europa.eu/en/eurostat-yearbook-95-pbCA8193204/ Contains information on historical trends in living standards in various European countries]\n* [http://primary-sources.eui.eu/ European History Primary Sources] Online access to primary sources for historians\n* {{cite web |title=History of Europe |url= http://www.nypl.org/collections/nypl-recommendations/guides?field_subject_taxonomy_value=604 |author=New York Public Library |location=New York |work=Research Guides |author-link = New York Public Library}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131005005904/http://www.vistorica.com/eng/persongroups/1500%2C2000%2Ceuropean%2Call.html Vistorica \u2013 Timelines of European modern history]\n\n{{History of Europe}}\n{{European history by country}}\n{{Europe topics (small)}}\n{{History by continent}}\n\n{{short description|History of Europe from the beginnings of recorded history}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Europe}}\n[[Category:History of Europe| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rosenborg BK Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrehistory of Europe:Updated section by adding a relevant caption to an image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Europe"}
{"title_page": "Sherlock (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|British crime drama television series, first broadcast in 2010}}\n{{For|other series about Sherlock Holmes|Sherlock Holmes (disambiguation)#Television}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Sherlock\n| image                    = Sherlock titlecard.jpg\n| alt                      = A view of the London skyline, with the word \"Sherlock\" in black letters\n| caption                  = Title card\n| genre                    = [[Crime film|Crime]]\n| creator                  = {{Plain list|\n* [[Mark Gatiss]]\n* [[Steven Moffat]]}}\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Canon of Sherlock Holmes|Sherlock Holmes]]''|[[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]}}\n| writer                   = {{Plain list|\n* Mark Gatiss\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]]}}\n| starring                 = {{Plain list|\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]]\n* [[Martin Freeman]]\n* [[Rupert Graves]]\n* [[Una Stubbs]]\n* Mark Gatiss\n* [[Louise Brealey]]\n* [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]]\n* [[Amanda Abbington]]\n}}\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David Arnold]]\n* [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]]\n}}\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 4\n| num_episodes             = 13\n| list_episodes            = List of Sherlock episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Mark Gatiss\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Beryl Vertue]]\n* [[Rebecca Eaton]]\n* Bethan Jones\n* [[Sue Vertue]]\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Unbulleted list|Sue Vertue|Elaine Cameron }}\n| editor                   = {{Unbulleted list|Charlie Phillips|Mali Evans|[[Tim Porter]]|Yan Miles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/news/2015/sherlock-editor-yan-miles-wins-an-eddie-award/|title=Sherlock editor Yan Miles wins an Eddie Award|website=Hartswood Films|access-date=3 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104074906/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/news/2015/sherlock-editor-yan-miles-wins-an-eddie-award/|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| cinematography           = {{Unbulleted list|[[Fabian Wagner]]|Steve Lawes}}\n| camera                   = Single camera\n| runtime                  = 85\u201390 minutes\n| company                  = {{Unbulleted list|[[Hartswood Films]]|[[BBC Cymru Wales|BBC Wales]]|[[WGBH-TV|WGBH]]}}\n| channel                  = {{Unbulleted list|[[BBC One]]|[[BBC HD]] (2010)|[[BBC One HD]] (2012\u2013present) |[[PBS]] (2010\u2013present)}}\n| picture_format           = [[576i50]]<br />[[1080i50]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|7|25|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2017|1|15|df=y}}<!-- Per the documentation at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_television, for the \"last_aired\" parameter: \"In some cases the fate of a program might be uncertain, for example if there are no announcements that a show has been renewed. If such a program has not aired a new episode in 12 months, \"present\" can be changed to the date the last episode aired, using {{End date}}. This does not imply the series has been cancelled, rather that the program \"last aired\" on that date. This is to prevent programs from being listed as \"present\" in perpetuity.\" -->\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws\n| production_website       = https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/sherlock/\n| production_website_title = PBS Official Website\n}}\n'''''Sherlock''''' is a British [[Crime film|crime]] television series based on [[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]'s [[Sherlock Holmes]] detective stories. Created by [[Steven Moffat]] and [[Mark Gatiss]], it stars [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] as Sherlock Holmes and [[Martin Freeman]] as [[Dr. Watson|Doctor John Watson]]. 13 episodes have been produced, with four three-part series airing from 2010 to 2017, and a special episode that aired on 1 January 2016. The series is set in the present day, while the one-off special features a Victorian period fantasy resembling the original Holmes stories. ''Sherlock'' is produced by the British network [[BBC]], along with [[Hartswood Films]], with Moffat, Gatiss, [[Sue Vertue]] and [[Rebecca Eaton]] serving as executive producers. The series is supported by the American station [[WGBH-TV]] Boston for its ''[[Masterpiece (TV series)|Masterpiece]]'' [[anthology series]] on [[PBS]], where it also airs in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/about/blogs/news/masterpiece-and-pbs-announce-new-sherlock-special-to-premiere-on-january-1/|title=MASTERPIECE and PBS Announce New \"Sherlock\" Special to Premiere on January 1|work=PBS|date=25 October 2015|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703001255/http://www.pbs.org/about/blogs/news/masterpiece-and-pbs-announce-new-sherlock-special-to-premiere-on-january-1|archive-date=3 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/pbs-bbc-co-production-deal-1201408869/|title=PBS & BBC Ink Multi-Title Co-Production Deal|work=Variety|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818001325/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/pbs-bbc-co-production-deal-1201408869/|archive-date=18 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/bbc-pbs-renew-masterpiece-partnership-14482/|title=BBC, PBS Renew 'Masterpiece' Partnership|work=The Wrap|date=22 February 2010|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019233657/http://www.thewrap.com/bbc-pbs-renew-masterpiece-partnership-14482/|archive-date=19 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The series is primarily filmed in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], with [[Gower Street, London|North Gower Street]] in [[London]] used for exterior shots of Holmes and Watson's [[221B Baker Street]] residence.\n\n''Sherlock'' has been praised for the quality of its writing, acting, and direction. It has been [[List of awards and nominations received by Sherlock|nominated for numerous awards]] including [[Emmy Award|Emmys]], [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTAs]] and a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]], winning several awards across a variety of categories. The show won in three categories at the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Cumberbatch, [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Freeman and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special]] for Moffat. Two years later, it won [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]]. In addition, the show was also honoured with a [[Peabody Award]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/masterpiece-sherlock-a-study-in-pink |title=Masterpiece: Sherlock: A Study in Pink (PBS) |website=Peabody Awards |date=May 2011 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8KuuOqD?url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/masterpiece-sherlock-a-study-in-pink |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series became the UK's most watched drama series since 2001.<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-22/sherlock-is-most-watched-drama-series-for-over-a-decade|title=Sherlock series 3 is most watched BBC drama series for over a decade. An average of almost 12 million people tuned into the third series of the detective drama on BBC1|last=Jones|first=Paul|work=Radio Times|date=22 January 2014}}</ref> ''Sherlock'' has been sold to 180 territories.<ref name=\"S5Lang\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jNzeuzYPiLc|title=Sherlock in five languages \u2013 BBC Worldwide Showcase|date=23 February 2012|work=YouTube|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502012133/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jNzeuzYPiLc|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll of the series have been released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]], alongside [[tie-in]] editions of selected original Conan Doyle stories and an original soundtrack composed by [[David Arnold]] and [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]]. In January 2014, the show launched its official [[mobile app]] called ''Sherlock: The Network''.<ref name=\"Jeffrey\">{{cite web|last=Jeffrey|first=Morgan|title=Sherlock: The Network app: 'It's a bit of Cumberbatch in your pocket'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tech/s129/sherlock/news/a545410/sherlock-the-network-app-its-a-bit-of-cumberbatch-in-your-pocket.html|publisher=Digital Spy|access-date=22 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122054400/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tech/s129/sherlock/news/a545410/sherlock-the-network-app-its-a-bit-of-cumberbatch-in-your-pocket.html|archive-date=22 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"itunes.apple.com\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/sherlock-the-network/id734800854?mt=8|title=Sherlock: The Network. Official App of the hit TV detective series|author=The Digital Development Factory Pty Ltd|date=20 January 2014|work=App Store|access-date=22 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305100822/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/sherlock-the-network/id734800854?mt=8|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Premise ==\n''Sherlock'' depicts \"consulting detective\" [[Sherlock Holmes]] ([[Benedict Cumberbatch]]) solving various mysteries in modern-day London. Holmes is assisted by his [[roommate|flatmate]] and friend, [[Dr. Watson|Dr. John Watson]] ([[Martin Freeman]]), who has returned from [[Operation Herrick|military service in Afghanistan]] with the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]. Although [[Metropolitan Police Service]] [[Inspector Lestrade|Detective Inspector Greg Lestrade]] ([[Rupert Graves]]) and others are suspicious of Holmes at first, over time, his exceptional intellect and bold powers of observation persuade them of his value. In part through Watson's [[blog]] documenting their adventures, Holmes becomes a reluctant celebrity with the press reporting on his cases and eccentric personal life. Both ordinary people and the British government ask for his help.\n\nAlthough the series depicts a variety of crimes and perpetrators, Holmes' conflict with [[Archenemy|nemesis]] [[Professor Moriarty|Jim Moriarty]] ([[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]]) is a recurring feature. [[List of Sherlock characters|Molly Hooper]] ([[Louise Brealey]]), a [[Pathology|pathologist]] at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital|St. Bart's Hospital]], occasionally assists Holmes in his cases. Other recurring roles include [[Una Stubbs]] as [[Minor Sherlock Holmes characters|Mrs. Hudson]], Holmes and Watson's landlady, and series co-creator [[Mark Gatiss]] as Holmes' elder brother [[Mycroft Holmes|Mycroft]].\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Conception and development ===\nSteven Moffat and Mark Gatiss, Sherlock Holmes fans with experience of adapting or using [[Victorian literature]] for television, devised the concept of the series.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /><ref name= \"Parker\">{{cite news |last= Parker |first= Robin |date= 23 August 2008 |url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/08/doctor_whos_moffat_to_pen_modern_sherlock_holmes.html |title= Doctor Who's Moffat to pen modern Sherlock Holmes |format= subscription access |work= [[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]] |publisher= Emap Media |accessdate= 27 December 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081202221914/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/08/doctor_whos_moffat_to_pen_modern_sherlock_holmes.html |archive-date= 2 December 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat had previously adapted the ''[[Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde]]'' for the 2007 series ''[[Jekyll (TV series)|Jekyll]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Walton |title=The weekend on television |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/06/18/nosplit/bvtv18last.xml |work=The Telegraph |date=18 June 2007 |accessdate=28 July 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021215855/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2007%2F06%2F18%2Fnosplit%2Fbvtv18last.xml |archive-date=21 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> while Gatiss had written the [[Charles Dickens|Dickensian]] ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[The Unquiet Dead]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Gatiss |first = Mark |authorlink=Mark Gatiss |title=Doctor Who: The Shooting Scripts | publisher=[[BBC Books]] |year=2005 |isbn=0-563-48641-4}}</ref> Moffat and Gatiss, both ''Doctor Who'' writers, discussed plans for a Holmes adaptation during their numerous train journeys to [[Cardiff]] where ''Doctor Who'' production is based.<ref>{{cite news|last= Bevan|first= Nathan|date= 15 January 2009|url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/01/15/benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman-star-in-new-bbc-sherlock-holmes-drama-filmed-in-cardiff-91466-22695776/|title= Benedict Cumberbatch, Martin Freeman star in new BBC Sherlock Holmes drama filmed in Cardiff|work= South Wales Echo|publisher= Western Mail and Echo|access-date= 26 July 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100315154446/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/01/15/benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman-star-in-new-bbc-sherlock-holmes-drama-filmed-in-cardiff-91466-22695776/|archive-date= 15 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> While they were in [[Monte Carlo]] for an awards ceremony, producer [[Sue Vertue]], who is married to Moffat, encouraged Moffat and Gatiss to develop the project themselves before another creative team had the same idea.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\">Sue Vertue, Steven Moffat and Mark Gatiss. DVD audio commentary for \"A Study in Pink\"</ref> Moffat and Gatiss invited Stephen Thompson to write for the series in September 2008.<ref name=\"memoirs\">Thompson, Steve \"Introduction\" In: {{cite book | series =Sherlock | title = [[The Memoirs of Sherlock Holmes]] |first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher = BBC Books | year=2012 |isbn=1-84990-406-5|origyear= 1894 |pages = vii\u2013ix}}</ref>\n\nGatiss has criticised recent television adaptations of the Conan Doyle stories as \"too reverential and too slow\", aiming instead to be as irreverent to the [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] as the [[Sherlock Holmes (1939 film series)|1930s and 1940s films]] starring [[Basil Rathbone]] and [[Nigel Bruce]], which were mostly set in the then-contemporary [[interwar]] era.<ref name = \"thorpe\" /> Benedict Cumberbatch's Sherlock uses modern technology, such as texting, the internet and [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] to solve crimes.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> [[Paul McGuigan (filmmaker)|Paul McGuigan]], who directed two episodes of ''Sherlock'', says that this is in keeping with Conan Doyle's character, pointing out that \"[i]n the books he would use any device possible and he was always in the lab doing experiments. It's just a modern day version of it. He will use the tools that are available to him today in order to find things out.\"<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news |title=Times have changed but crimes are the same for new Sherlock Holmes |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/times-have-changed-but-crimes-are-the-same-for-new-sherlock-holmes-1.1042129 |first=Brian |last=Pendreigh |date=19 July 2010 |work=The Herald |accessdate=20 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67V3OiHY4?url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/times-have-changed-but-crimes-are-the-same-for-new-sherlock-holmes-1.1042129 |archive-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe update maintains various elements of the original stories, such as the [[221B Baker Street|Baker Street address]] and Holmes' adversary Moriarty.<ref name=\"telegraph19122008\" /> Some of these elements are transposed to the present day: for example, Martin Freeman's Watson has returned from [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|military service in Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news| agency = AP| date = 16 August 2009| url = http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/2009/08/16/life-outside-the-office-for-martin-freeman-91466-24449418/| title = Life outside The Office for Martin Freeman| work = Wales on Sunday| publisher = Western Mail and Echo| access-date = 24 August 2009| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120118193611/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/2009/08/16/life-outside-the-office-for-martin-freeman-91466-24449418/| archive-date = 18 January 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> While discussing the fact that the original Watson was invalided home after serving in the [[Second Anglo-Afghan War]] (1878\u201380), Gatiss realised that \"[i]t is the same war now, I thought. The same unwinnable war.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" />\n\n''Sherlock'' was announced as a single 60-minute drama production at the [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]] in August 2008, with broadcast set for mid- to late 2009.<ref name = \"telegraph19122008\" /> The intention was to produce a series of six 60-minute episodes should the pilot prove to be successful.<ref name = \"s1ep1-comm\" /><ref name=\"telegraph19122008\">{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3852882/BBC-to-make-a-modern-day-Sherlock-Holmes.html |title= BBC to make a modern-day Sherlock Holmes |date= 19 December 2008 |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate= 20 July 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100315161707/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3852882/BBC-to-make-a-modern-day-Sherlock-Holmes.html |archive-date= 15 March 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first version of the pilot\u2014reported by ''[[The Guardian]]'' to have cost \u00a3800,000\u2014led to rumours within the BBC and wider media that ''Sherlock'' was a potential disaster.<ref name = \"Mail-yearend\" /><ref name =\"lawson-rebirth\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Lawson |authorlink=Mark Lawson |title=The rebirth of Sherlock |date=2 September 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/sep/02/sherlock-mark-lawson |work=The Guardian |accessdate=7 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002154049/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/sep/02/sherlock-mark-lawson |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The BBC decided not to transmit the pilot, requesting a reshoot and a total of three 90-minute episodes.<ref name=\"Mail-yearend\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/dec/26/christmas-tv-replay-2010-downloads|title=Replay the best of 2010|last=Heritage|first=Stuart|date=24 December 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=18 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002165217/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/dec/26/christmas-tv-replay-2010-downloads|archive-date=2 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name= \"lawson-rebirth\" /> The original pilot was included on the DVD of the first series. During the audio commentary, the creative team said that the BBC were \"very happy\" with the pilot but asked them to change the format.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Critic [[Mark Lawson]] observes that the pilot that was on air was \"substantially expanded and rewritten, and completely reimagined in look, pace and sound\".<ref name=\"lawson-rebirth\" /> In July 2009, the BBC drama department announced plans for three 90-minute episodes, to be broadcast in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last= McMahon |first= Kate |date= 14 July 2009 |url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc1-unveils-new-dramas/5003543.article |title= BBC1 unveils new dramas |format= subscription access |work= Broadcast |publisher= Emap Media |accessdate= 21 July 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090721013719/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc1-unveils-new-dramas/5003543.article |archive-date= 21 July 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat had previously announced that if a series of ''Sherlock'' was commissioned, Gatiss would take over the duties of executive producer so that he could concentrate on producing ''Doctor Who''.<ref name=\"Parker\" />\n\n=== Cast and characters ===\n{{Main|List of Sherlock characters}}\nMoffat and Vertue became interested in casting Cumberbatch as the title character after watching his performance in the 2007 film ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]''. The actor was cast after [[Audition|reading the script]] for the creative team.<ref name=\"unlocking\">\"Unlocking Sherlock\", documentary included on the Series 1 DVD/Blu-Ray release</ref> \"Cumberbatch\", says ''The Guardian'', \"has a reputation for playing odd, brilliant men very well, and his Holmes is cold, techie, slightly [[Asperger syndrome|Aspergerish]]\".<ref name=\"Mitchison\">{{cite news |first=Amanda |last=Mitchison |title=Benedict Cumberbatch on playing Sherlock Holmes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/17/benedict-cumberbatch-sherlock-holmes |work=The Guardian |date=17 July 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930144744/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/17/benedict-cumberbatch-sherlock-holmes |archive-date=30 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cumberbatch said, \"There's a great charge you get from playing him, because of the volume of words in your head and the speed of thought\u2014you really have to make your connections incredibly fast. He is one step ahead of the audience and of anyone around him with normal intellect. They can't quite fathom where his leaps are taking him.\"<ref name=\"Mitchison\" /> [[Piers Wenger]], head of drama at [[BBC Cymru Wales]], described the series' rendering of Sherlock as \"a dynamic [[superhero]] in a modern world, an arrogant, genius sleuth driven by a desire to prove himself cleverer than the perpetrator and the police\u2014everyone in fact\".<ref name=\"telegraph19122008\" /> Addressing changing social attitudes and broadcasting regulations, Cumberbatch's Holmes replaced the [[Pipe smoking|pipe]] with multiple [[nicotine patch]]es.<ref name=\"herald\" /> The writers believed that Sherlock should not talk like \"a completely modern person\", says Moffat, but were initially intent that \"he never sounded like he's giving a lecture\". Moffat turned the character \"more Victorian\" in the second series, capitalising more on Cumberbatch's \"beautiful voice\" to make it sound like \"he's giving a lecture\".<ref name=\"ds-moff-trf\">{{cite web |title='Sherlock' Steven Moffat interview: 'Holmes might not survive' |date=11 January 2012 |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a359357/sherlock-steven-moffat-interview-holmes-might-not-survive.html |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=13 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113013556/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a359357/sherlock-steven-moffat-interview-holmes-might-not-survive.html |archive-date=13 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{multiple image|total_width=320|image1=Benedict Cumberbatch filming Sherlock cropped2.jpg|image2=Martin Freeman filming Sherlock cropped2.jpg|footer=[[Benedict Cumberbatch]] (left) and [[Martin Freeman]] (right) during filming of the first series}}\nIn an interview with ''[[The Observer]]'', co-creator Mark Gatiss says that they experienced more difficulty finding the right actor to play [[Dr. Watson|Dr. John Watson]] than they had for the title character.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Producer Sue Vertue said, \"Benedict was the only person we actually saw for [the part of] Sherlock... Once Benedict was there it was really just making sure we got the chemistry for John [Watson]\u2014and I think you get it as soon as they come into the room, you can see that they work together\".<ref name=\"guard-renew\" /> Several actors auditioned for the part of Watson,<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> and Martin Freeman eventually took the role. Steven Moffat said that [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] was the first to audition unsuccessfully. He was rejected for being too \"barmy\", as the producers required someone \"straighter\" for Watson.<ref name=\"mattsmith\">{{cite news|last=French|first=Dan|date=4 February 2010|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctorwho/news/a201372/matt-smith-rejected-for-bbcs-sherlock.html|title=Matt Smith rejected for BBC's 'Sherlock'|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=4 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100207081631/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctorwho/news/a201372/matt-smith-rejected-for-bbcs-sherlock.html|archive-date=7 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after, Moffat cast Smith as the [[Eleventh Doctor]] in ''Doctor Who''.<ref name=\"mattsmith\" />\n\nThe writers said that Freeman's casting developed the way in which Cumberbatch played Holmes.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> The theme of friendship appealed to both Gatiss and Moffat.<ref name=\"moff-study\">Moffat, Steven \"Introduction\" In: {{cite book |title=Sherlock: A Study in Scarlet|first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher=Random House |year=2011|pages=xi\u2013xii |isbn=1-84990-366-2}}</ref> Gatiss asserted the importance of achieving the correct tone for the character. \"Watson is not an idiot, although it's true that Conan Doyle always took the piss out of him,\" said Gatiss. \"But only an idiot would surround himself with idiots.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Moffat said that Freeman is \"the sort of opposite of Benedict in everything except the amount of talent... Martin finds a sort of poetry in the ordinary man. I love the fastidious realism of everything he does.\"<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Freeman describes his character as a \"moral compass\" for Sherlock, who does not always consider the morality and ethics of his actions.<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\nRupert Graves was cast as DI Greg Lestrade. The writers referred to the character as \"Inspector Lestrade\" during development until Gatiss realised that in contemporary England the character would have the title \"Detective Inspector\". Moffat and Gatiss pointed out that Lestrade does not appear often in the stories and is quite inconsistently portrayed in them. They decided to go with the version that appeared in \"[[The Adventure of the Six Napoleons]]\": a man who is frustrated by Holmes but admires him, and whom Holmes considers as the best person at [[Scotland Yard]].<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Several candidates took a comedic tack in their auditions, but the creative team preferred the gravitas that Graves brought to the role.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> His first name is revealed to be Greg in \"The Hounds of Baskerville\".<ref name=\"s2ep2\">{{cite episode |title=The Hounds of Baskerville |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Mark Gatiss, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=8 January 2012 |seriesno=2 |number=2}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Scott made his first appearance as Jim Moriarty in \"The Great Game\". Moffat said, \"We knew what we wanted to do with Moriarty from the very beginning. Moriarty is usually a rather dull, rather posh villain so we thought someone who was genuinely properly frightening. Someone who's an absolute psycho.\"<ref name=\"guard-renew\" /> Moffat and Gatiss were originally not going to put a confrontation between Moriarty and Holmes into these three episodes, but after seeing Scott's audition<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherlock creator: Andrew Scott\u2019s Moriarty audition was so good we re-wrote the episode for him|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-12/sherlock-creator-andrew-scotts-moriarty-audition-was-so-good-we-re-wrote-the-episode-for-him/|website=[[Radio Times]]|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=31 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100402/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-12/sherlock-creator-andrew-scotts-moriarty-audition-was-so-good-we-re-wrote-the-episode-for-him/|archive-date=1 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> they realised that they \"just had to do a confrontation scene. We had to do a version of the scene in '[[The Final Problem]]' in which the two archenemies meet each other.\"<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" />\n\nThe remainder of the regular cast includes Una Stubbs (who has known Cumberbatch since he was four years old, as she had worked with his mother [[Wanda Ventham]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/squidink/2012/05/q_a_with_una_stubbs.php?page=2|title=Q & A With Una Stubbs: The Joy of Victoria Sponges + Getting Sherlock Holmes to Eat|date=9 October 2014|work=LA Weekly|access-date=2 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192202/http://blogs.laweekly.com/squidink/2012/05/q_a_with_una_stubbs.php?page=2|archive-date=2 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Mrs. Hudson and co-creator Mark Gatiss as Mycroft Holmes.<ref name=\"bbcpressep2\">{{cite web |title=Network TV BBC Week 31: Sunday 1&nbsp;August 2010 |work=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk31/sun.shtml#sun_sherlock |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720160047/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk31/sun.shtml#sun_sherlock |archive-date=20 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Vinette Robinson]], [[Jonathan Aris]] and [[Louise Brealey]] play the recurring roles of Sergeant Sally Donovan, Philip Anderson and Molly Hooper, respectively.\n\n[[Amanda Abbington]], Freeman's then-real life partner, plays [[Mary Morstan]], Watson's girlfriend and eventual wife. In Series 3, [[Wanda Ventham]] and [[Timothy Carlton]], Cumberbatch's actual parents, are introduced as Sherlock and Mycroft's parents.\n\nGuest appearances included [[Phil Davis (actor)|Phil Davis]] as Jefferson Hope,<ref name=\"s1ep1\">{{cite episode |title=A Study in Pink |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Steven Moffat, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=25 July 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=1}}</ref> [[Paul Chequer]] as DI Dimmock,<ref name=\"s1ep2\">{{cite episode |title=The Blind Banker |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Stephen Thompson, dir. Euros Lyn |network=BBC |airdate=1 August 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=2}}</ref> [[Zoe Telford]] as Sarah,<ref name=\"s1ep2\" /> [[Gemma Chan]] as Soo Lin Yao,<ref name=\"s1ep2\" /> [[John Sessions]] as Kenny Prince,<ref name=\"s1ep3\">{{cite episode |title=The Great Game |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Mark Gatiss, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=8 August 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=3}}</ref> [[Haydn Gwynne]] as Miss Wenceslas,<ref name=\"s1ep3\" /> [[Deborah Moore]]<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\">Mark Gatiss, Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman. DVD audio commentary for \"The Great Game\"</ref> as one of Moriarty's victims and [[Peter Davison]] as the voice-over in the planetarium.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" /> Series two's \"[[A Scandal in Belgravia]]\" featured [[Lara Pulver]] as [[Irene Adler]],<ref name=\"telegraph=iplayer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9297689/Sherlock-episode-with-naked-Lara-Pulver-most-watched-show-on-BBC-iPlayer.html|title=Sherlock episode with naked Lara Pulver most watched show on BBC iPlayer|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=29 May 2012|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601223433/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9297689/Sherlock-episode-with-naked-Lara-Pulver-most-watched-show-on-BBC-iPlayer.html|archive-date=1 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> while \"[[The Hounds of Baskerville]]\" featured [[Russell Tovey]] as Henry Knight.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a327636/russell-tovey-to-appear-in-sherlock.html|title=Russell Tovey to appear in 'Sherlock'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=30 June 2011|accessdate=24 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716073510/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a327636/russell-tovey-to-appear-in-sherlock.html|archive-date=16 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final episode of series 2, the role of Rufus Bruhl was played by Edward Holtom, while [[Katherine Parkinson]] played journalist Kitty Riley. The first episode of series 3 featured [[Derren Brown]].\n\n=== Production design and filming ===\nThe show was produced by Hartswood Films for BBC Wales, while [[BBC Worldwide]] also provided co-production funding.<ref name=\"Parker\" /><ref>{{cite news|last= Clarke|first= Steve|date= 1 October 2009|url= https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009441.html?categoryId=3750&cs=1|title= Can Holmes solve co-prod mystery?|work= Variety|publisher= Reed Business Information|accessdate= 2 October 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091006143222/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009441.html?categoryid=3750&cs=1|archive-date= 6 October 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Production was also co-produced by [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]], a network of public-service broadcasters in the United States, for [[WGBH-TV]]'s ''[[Mystery!|Masterpiece Mystery!]]'' strand.<ref name=\"weisman\">{{cite news|last= Weisman |first=Jon|date= 22 February 2010|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118015609.html?categoryId=14&cs=1|title= PBS climbs 'Upstairs' with BBC|work= Variety|publisher= Reed Business Information|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"press12july\">{{cite web |author=BBC Press Office |date=12 July 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/07_july/12/sherlock.shtml |title=''Sherlock'' Press pack |accessdate=12 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715091537/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/07_july/12/sherlock.shtml |archive-date=15 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming of the pilot episode, written by Moffat and directed by [[Coky Giedroyc]], commenced in January 2009.<ref>{{cite press release |title=BBC Drama announces 'Sherlock', a new crime drama for BBC One |publisher=BBC Press Office |date=19 December 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/12_december/19/sherlock.shtml |accessdate=27 December 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I1ym6vEq?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/12_december/19/sherlock.shtml |archive-date=11 July 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following January (2010), the first set of three episodes entered production. Paul McGuigan directed the first and third episodes and [[Euros Lyn]] directed the second.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=Hartswood Films|date= January 2010|url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/pdf/sherlock-start-of-shoot-press-release.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716174250/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/pdf/sherlock-start-of-shoot-press-release.pdf|archivedate= 16 July 2011|format=PDF|title= Filming Begins on 'Sherlock'|accessdate=28 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Levine|first=Nick|date=17 April 2010|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/tubetalk/a214862/mark-gatiss-talks-who-sherlock.html|title=Mark Gatiss talks 'Who', 'Sherlock'|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=28 May 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8J9IGHv?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/tubetalk/a214862/mark-gatiss-talks-who-sherlock.html|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The three episodes were filmed in reverse order of their broadcast.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" />\n[[File:Shooting Sherlock.JPG|thumb|left|[[North Gower Street]] in London was used for exterior shots of the location of Holmes' \"Baker Street\" residence<ref name=\"londontown\" />|alt=A street, with crew members looking towards a caf\u00e9 and a house]]\nGatiss says that they wanted to \"fetishise modern London in the way that the period versions fetishise Victorian London\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Production was based at Hartswood Films' Cardiff production unit, Hartswood Films West, which was opened in late 2009 to take advantage of the BBC's planned [[Cardiff Bay]] \"drama village\". Production of the first two series was based at [[Upper Boat Studios]], where ''Doctor Who'' had been produced.<ref>{{cite news|last= Parker|first= Robin|date= 20 August 2009|url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/indies/hartswood-set-to-develop-projects-from-welsh-office/5004700.article|title= Hartswood set to develop projects from Welsh office|format= subscription access|work= Broadcast|publisher= Emap Media|accessdate= 20 August 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120405095945/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/indies/hartswood-set-to-develop-projects-from-welsh-office/5004700.article|archive-date= 5 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Upstairs\">{{cite web |first= Maggie |last=Brown |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/30501/upstairs-downstairs-the-return-of-a-classic | title= Upstairs, Downstairs: The Return of a Classic |work=[[The Stage]] | date= 3 December 2010 | accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> Cardiff was more economical than in London, with some good matches for parts of London.<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Some architecture could not be faked, so location shooting in the English capital was necessary.<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> The location shots for 221B Baker Street were filmed at 187 [[North Gower Street]]<ref name=\"londontown\">{{Cite journal|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonBlog/Nelsons/8800/Holmes_sweet_Holmes |title=Holmes sweet Holmes |date=26 July 2010 |publisher=London Town |first=Sadie |last=Nelson |journal=Nelson's Column |accessdate=4 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803171413/http://londontown.com/LondonBlog/Nelsons/8800/Holmes_sweet_Holmes |archivedate=3 August 2010 |df= }}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 Baker Street was impractical because of heavy traffic, and the number of things labelled \"Sherlock Holmes\", which would need to be disguised.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" /> Executive producer [[Beryl Vertue]] explains how it was important to design the entirety of Sherlock's flat as a contemporary set, yet still convey his eccentricity. He would not, she says, live somewhere \"too suburban\" or \"too modern\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\nSpeedy's, the sandwich shop below the flat used as Holmes' residence, reported a sharp rise in new customers who recognised it from the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rackl|first=Lori|title=Hunting for \u2018Sherlock\u2019 at Speedy\u2019s, a London cafe|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2015/12/19/speedy-quick-rise-fame-elementary/mUib4MZQt6xvOc32qbMPFL/story.html|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Lynnette|title=Speedy's Cafe: Starring in 'Sherlock' is Part of the Family Business |url=https://www.popmatters.com/170857-speedys-cafe-starring-in-sherlock-is-part-of-the-family-business-2495761536.html|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|date=1 May 2013|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nCostumes for the pilot were designed by [[BAFTA Cymru]] award-winning costume designer Ray Holman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.costume-designer.co.uk/cv/sherlock/|title=Sherlock|publisher=Ray Holman website|accessdate=21 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805144529/http://www.costume-designer.co.uk/portfolio-items/sherlock-pilot/|archive-date=5 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Cumberbatch wore a \u00a31,000 [[Belstaff]] coat in the series.<ref name=\"indep-costume\" /> Sarah Arthur, the series' costume designer, explained how she achieved the detective's look. \"Holmes wouldn't have any interest in fashion so I went for classic suits with a modern twist: narrow-leg trousers and a two-button, slim-cut jacket. I also went for slim-cut shirts and a sweeping coat for all the action scenes\u2014it looks great against the London skyline.\"<ref name=\"indep-costume\">{{cite news |first1=Paul |last1=Bignell |first2=Rachel |last2=Shields |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/sherlock-chic-fashion-its-elementary-thanks-to-bbc-2046500.html |title=Sherlock chic! Fashion? It's elementary, thanks to BBC |work=The Independent |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=10 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022020124/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/sherlock-chic-fashion-its-elementary-thanks-to-bbc-2046500.html |archive-date=22 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe writers say that they did not want to force modernity onto the story.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> There were some creative challenges, such as the decision to include the sign \"221B\" on Holmes' front door. Gatiss and Moffat reflect that in the modern world the door would only display the number of the house, and there would be doorbells for each flat. The full house number is so iconic that they felt unable to change it.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> The writers also decided that the lead characters would address each other by their first names, rather than the traditional Holmes and Watson.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> This was also reflected in the title of the series. Director Paul McGuigan came up with the idea of putting text messages on the screen instead of having cut-away shots of a hand holding the phone.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" />\n\n[[File:Martin Freeman + Benedict Cumberbatch.JPG|thumb|[[Martin Freeman]] and [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] filming the third series of ''Sherlock'', August 2013]]\nThe producers found it difficult to coordinate the schedules of the principal players and Moffat and Gatiss for a second series. Cumberbatch and Freeman both worked on the 2012 film ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]'', and Moffat continued as ''Doctor Who''{{'}}s showrunner and head writer. In response to the time pressure, ''The Guardian'' asserted, the series \"features reworkings of three of Conan Doyle's most recognised tales\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> Gatiss says that there had been an argument for producing these tales over three years, but Moffat explained that they rejected \"deferred pleasure\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> The relationship between Holmes and Watson developed during the second series, with Watson being less amazed by Sherlock's deductive abilities; Watson acted as the primary detective in the second episode, \"The Hounds of Baskerville\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> The cast and production team were more confident during the second series' production following the positive audience and critical reaction to the first series.<ref name=\"ds-moff-trf\" /><ref name=\"uncovered\">\"Sherlock Uncovered\", documentary on ''Sherlock'' series 2 DVD/Blu-ray release</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nThe theme and [[incidental music]] were composed by [[David Arnold]] and [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]].<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Arnold explains that he and Price worked with the producers to \"come up with a central theme and character\" for the series, then found what was \"going to be the defining sound of this show\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Pieces were often constructed using [[synthesizer]]s, but the tracks used for the show were recorded using real musicians, Arnold says, to bring the music \"to life\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Similarly, Price comments that the musicians can adapt their performance of a [[film score|score]] by responding to footage from the show.<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{main|List of Sherlock episodes}}\nFour series, each consisting of three episodes, have been produced. The first series was initially broadcast in July and August 2010 on the BBC, later premiering on [[PBS|Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) in the United States in October 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest Sherlock Hears a 'Who'|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2010/10/22/arts/television/22sherlock.html |first=Mike |last=Hale |work=The New York Times |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref> A second series of three episodes was first broadcast in the UK in January 2012, and then in the U.S. during May 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Holmes and Watson, Back to Bantering |url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/05/05/arts/television/sherlock-returns-on-masterpiece-mystery.html |first=Neil |last=Genzlinger |work=The New York Times |date=4 May 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627235122/http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/05/05/arts/television/sherlock-returns-on-masterpiece-mystery.html |archive-date=27 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series premiered in the UK on 1 January 2014 and in the US on 19 January 2014. The series has been sold to 180 territories.<ref name=\"S5Lang\" /> A special episode premiered on 1 January 2016, on BBC One and PBS, marking the first time the series has aired on the same day in the UK and U.S.<ref name=\"SpecialAirdate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/24/sherlock-date|title=Sherlock finally gets return date, plus new full trailer|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=24 October 2015|accessdate=24 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025134601/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/24/sherlock-date|archive-date=25 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth series began airing on BBC One and PBS on 1 January 2017 and concluded on 15 January 2017.<ref name=\"S4Airdates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-06/full-schedule-of-sherlock-series-4-air-dates-confirmed|title=Full schedule of Sherlock series 4 air dates confirmed|author=Paul Jones|work=RadioTimes|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206235753/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-06/full-schedule-of-sherlock-series-4-air-dates-confirmed|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{:List of Sherlock episodes}}\n\n=== Series 1 (2010) ===\nThe first episode, \"[[A Study in Pink]]\", loosely based upon the first Sherlock Holmes novel ''[[A Study in Scarlet]]'', was written by Moffat and directed by Paul McGuigan. The story depicts the introduction of Sherlock to John, and them entering a [[Roommate|flatshare]] at Baker Street in London, and then their investigation into a series of deaths, initially believed to be suicides. Mycroft Holmes, Sherlock's older brother, played by [[Mark Gatiss]], also appears for the first time. The episode was first broadcast simultaneously on BBC One and BBC HD on 25 July 2010.<ref name=\"guard-ep1-fig\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Sweney |title=Sherlock Holmes more popular than Tom Cruise |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/26/sherlock-holmes-more-viewers-top-gear |work=The Guardian |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=4 August 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8K9JnQM?url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/26/sherlock-holmes-more-viewers-top-gear |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"press\">{{cite web |author=BBC Press Office |date=8 July 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk30/unplaced.shtml#unplaced_sherlock |title=\"Network TV BBC Week 30: Unplaced\" Press release |accessdate=14 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8JvGks0?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk30/unplaced.shtml#unplaced_sherlock |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe second episode, \"[[The Blind Banker]]\", was first broadcast on 1 August 2010. Written by [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]] and directed by Euros Lyn, the episode depicts Holmes being hired by an old university acquaintance to investigate a mysterious break-in at a bank in the [[City of London]].<ref name=\"guard-ep2-fig\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Deans |title=Sherlock on the case with 6.4m |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/02/sherlock-bbc1-tv-ratings |work=The Guardian |date=2 August 2010 |accessdate=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801234841/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/02/sherlock-bbc1-tv-ratings |archive-date=1 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first series concluded with \"[[The Great Game (Sherlock)|The Great Game]]\", first broadcast on 8 August 2010. The episode introduces the character of archenemy James Moriarty (played by Andrew Scott) to the series, who sets Holmes deadlines to solve a series of apparently unrelated cases. Written by Mark Gatiss and directed by McGuigan, \"The Great Game\" ends with a cliffhanger in which Sherlock and Moriarty reach a standoff involving a bomb attached to a vest removed moments earlier from Watson.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Sherlock |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/09/sherlock-benedict-cumberbatch-tv-review |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 April 2011 |date=9 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922145409/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/09/sherlock-benedict-cumberbatch-tv-review |archive-date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 2 (2012) ===\nAfter the high ratings for \"A Study in Pink\", the BBC was reportedly eager to produce more episodes.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC 'keen to film more Sherlock' |first=Christian |last=Tobin |date=27 July 2010 |work=Digital Spy |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a251236/bbc-keen-to-film-more-sherlock.html |accessdate=28 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727231812/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a251236/bbc-keen-to-film-more-sherlock.html |archive-date=27 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 10 August 2010, it was confirmed that ''Sherlock'' had been renewed for a second series.<ref name=\"guard-renew\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/10/sherlock-second-series-bbc |title=Sherlock to return for second series |last=Frost |first=Vicky |date=10 August 2010 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=10 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922010019/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/10/sherlock-second-series-bbc |archive-date=22 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the 2011 convention, Gatiss confirmed which stories would be adapted, and that the writers of the first series would each write an episode for series two.<ref name=\"ign-kapow\">{{cite web |first=Leigh |last=Singer |title=Kapow! 11: Ideal Holmes: Mark Gatiss on the new series of Sherlock and Doctor Who |date=10 April 2011 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/116/1160905p1.html |work=IGN.com |accessdate=26 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110413151336/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/116/1160905p1.html |archive-date=13 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Acknowledging that \"[[A Scandal in Bohemia]]\", \"[[The Hound of the Baskervilles]]\" and \"[[The Final Problem]]\" are amongst the best-known Holmes stories, Gatiss explained, \"We knew after having a successful first run that the natural order would be to do three of the most famous [stories].\"<ref name=\"ign-kapow\" /> \"There's the question of how to go out on a cliffhanger and then the thematic things of the three stories, where we were trying to get to and what Sherlock and John's relationship is a little further on. You can't just go back to: 'You have no emotions.' 'I don't care.' You've got to move on somewhere and make sure the other characters have something of a journey too.\"<ref name=\"ign-kapow\" /> Paul McGuigan directed the first two episodes,<ref>{{cite news |title=Director's cut: How Hollywood director witnessed real gore for new tv drama |date=7 March 2011 |first=Brian |last=McIver |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2011/03/07/director-s-cut-how-hollywood-director-witnessed-real-gore-for-new-tv-drama-86908-22972460/ |work=Daily Record |publisher=Scottish Daily Record and Sunday Mail Ltd. |accessdate=26 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324071116/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2011/03/07/director-s-cut-how-hollywood-director-witnessed-real-gore-for-new-tv-drama-86908-22972460/ |archive-date=24 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''Doctor Who'' director [[Toby Haynes]] handled the last one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96fgOz0uDzs|title=Video: Doctor Who at Wondercon 2011 (View from 36:35)|work=YouTube|accessdate=20 April 2011|quote=So what's next for you?\" \"I'm doing ''Sherlock''.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053827/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96fgOz0uDzs|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The second series of three 90-minute episodes was initially planned to air in late 2011,<ref>\n{{cite web |title=New commissions and return of Sherlock for BBC One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/08_august/28/bbcone.shtml |work=BBC Press Office |date=28 August 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916083512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/08_august/28/bbcone.shtml |archive-date=16 September 2010 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> but was delayed until early January 2012.\n\n\"[[A Scandal in Belgravia]]\", written by Steven Moffat and directed by Paul McGuigan, was first broadcast on 1 January 2012. Loosely based on \"A Scandal in Bohemia\", the episode depicts Holmes's quest to retrieve compromising photos of a minor royal held on the camera phone of Irene Adler ([[Lara Pulver]]), a ruthless and brilliant [[dominatrix#Professional|dominatrix]] who also trades in classified information extracted from her rich and powerful clients.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 January 2012 |title=Last Night's TV: Sherlock, BBC 1 |newspaper=The Independent |first=Tom |last=Sutcliffe |authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster) |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv-sherlock-bbc-1-6283989.html |accessdate=4 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108021204/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv-sherlock-bbc-1-6283989.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Barts.jpg|thumb|The resolution of Sherlock's faked suicide from the roof of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] in London attracted speculation in social media and newspapers.]]\nMark Gatiss wrote \"[[The Hounds of Baskerville]]\", which investigates the strange activities at a military base. Aware that ''The Hound of the Baskervilles'', first published in 1902, was one of the most famous of Conan Doyle's original stories, Gatiss felt a greater responsibility to include familiar elements of the story than he does when adapting the lesser-known stories.<ref name=\"gat-ds\">{{cite web |title='Sherlock' Mark Gatiss Q&A: 'Horror is a big part of Sherlock Holmes' |date=5 January 2012 |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a358335/sherlock-mark-gatiss-qa-horror-is-a-big-part-of-sherlock-holmes.html |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=8 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108065805/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a358335/sherlock-mark-gatiss-qa-horror-is-a-big-part-of-sherlock-holmes.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sherlock writer Steven Moffat furious with sexist claim |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2012/01/04/sherlock-writer-steven-moffat-furious-with-sexist-claim-91466-30062866/2/ |first=Simon |last=Gaskell |work=Wales Online |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113091342/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2012/01/04/sherlock-writer-steven-moffat-furious-with-sexist-claim-91466-30062866/2/ |archivedate=13 January 2012 |df= }}</ref> Russell Tovey appeared as Henry Knight, a man whose father was ripped apart by a gigantic hound on [[Dartmoor]] 20 years earlier. Directed by McGuigan, the episode was first broadcast on 8 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Borgen; Sherlock |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/07/tv-review-borgen-sherlock |date=7 January 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=8 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104233313/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/07/tv-review-borgen-sherlock |archive-date=4 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe second series concluded with \"[[The Reichenbach Fall]]\". Steve Thompson wrote the episode, which was directed by Toby Haynes, who had previously directed many of Moffat's ''Doctor Who'' episodes. First broadcast on 15 January 2012, the episode follows Moriarty's plot to discredit and kill Sherlock Holmes, concluding with Holmes appearing to die by suicide.<ref name=\"missed-clues\" /> The episode was inspired by Conan Doyle's story \"The Final Problem\", in which Holmes and Moriarty are presumed to have fallen to their deaths from the [[Reichenbach Falls]] in [[Switzerland]]. Moffat felt that he and co-creator Gatiss had outdone Conan Doyle in their version of Holmes' fall and Moffat added that, in that much-discussed sequence, there was still \"a clue everybody's missed\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title=Sherlock: vital missing clue behind death fall |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/sherlock-vital-missing-clue-death-fall |date=20 January 2012 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=28 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809132914/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/sherlock-vital-missing-clue-death-fall |archive-date=9 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Christmas mini-episode (2013) ===\nBBC One premiered a seven-minute ''Sherlock'' mini-episode over the 2013 Christmas period entitled \"Many Happy Returns\". The episode is available via [[BBC iPlayer]], [[BBC Red Button]] service, and BBC's [[YouTube]] channel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwntNANJCOE|title=Sherlock Mini-Episode: Many Happy Returns&nbsp;\u2014 Sherlock Series 3 Prequel&nbsp;\u2014 BBC One|website=BBC Youtube channel|date=24 December 2013|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026133016/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwntNANJCOE|archive-date=26 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and acts as a prequel to the third series.\n\nThe synopsis for the episode reads \"Sherlock has been gone for two years. But someone isn't quite convinced that he's dead.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws|title=''Sherlock'' profile, BBC One|work=BBC|access-date=29 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105043656/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws|archive-date=5 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The 'someone' turns out to be [[List of Sherlock characters#Philip Anderson|Anderson]], the forensics technician from series 1 and 2 (who has now lost his job due to his obsessive conviction that the detective still lives). He had a long-standing mistrust of Sherlock, yet is now one of the few people who believes Sherlock is alive, and throughout the episode is trying to convince Lestrade. Anderson tracks him via various mysterious events from Tibet to New Delhi to Germany in which he seems to be involved and points out that the incidents are getting progressively closer to London.\n\n=== Series 3 (2014) ===\nAfter the end of the final episode of the second series, Moffat and Gatiss both announced on Twitter that a third series had been commissioned at the same time as series two,<ref name=\"bbc20120116\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock to return for third series |date=16 January 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16573066 |work=BBC News |accessdate=16 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116180916/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16573066 |archive-date=16 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a part of the resolution to \"The Reichenbach Fall\" was filmed concurrently with series two.<ref name=\"missed-clues\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title='There is a clue everybody's missed': Sherlock writer Steven Moffat interviewed |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211731/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Without revealing whether Moriarty also faked his own death at the end of series two, Moffat suggested that Moriarty will not feature heavily in future series of ''Sherlock''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steven Moffat: expect new Sherlock villains |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-01/steven-moffat-expect-new-sherlock-villains |date=1 March 2012 |work=Radio Times |publisher=Immediate Media Company Limited |accessdate=13 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303224238/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-01/steven-moffat-expect-new-sherlock-villains |archive-date=3 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Sherlock' creator: 'Moriarty won't return' |url=https://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/sherlock-creator-moriarty-wont-return/261748 |date=2 March 2012 |work=NME |accessdate=13 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304201201/http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/sherlock-creator-moriarty-wont-return/261748 |archive-date=4 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[The Empty Hearse]]\", written by Mark Gatiss and directed by Jeremy Lovering, is the first episode of Series 3 and was first broadcast on 1 January 2014. Inspired by \"[[The Adventure of the Empty House]]\" by [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]], the episode follows Sherlock Holmes' return to London and reunion with John Watson, and their subsequent solving of an underground terrorist network. The episode achieved an official rating of 12.72&nbsp;million viewers,<ref>{{Cite web|title = BARB|url = http://www.barb.co.uk/|website = www.barb.co.uk|access-date = 5 February 2016|archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/5gJ2i7uOI?url=http://www.barb.co.uk/|archive-date = 25 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> making it the [[Highest rated drama episodes in the United Kingdom in 2014|highest rated drama episode shown on UK television in 2014]].\n\nIn \"[[The Sign of Three]]\", written by Stephen Thompson, Mark Gatiss and [[Steven Moffat]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03ny7ng | title=The Sign of Three, Series 3 Episode 2 | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=bbc.co.uk | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102140549/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03ny7ng | archive-date=2 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> Watson and Mary Morstan<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-01/sherlock-series-3-episode-2-the-sign-of-three-programme-guide | title=Sherlock series 3 episode 2 The Sign of Three programme guide | publisher=[[Radio Times]] | work=radiotimes.com | date=1 January 2014 | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103070719/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-01/sherlock-series-3-episode-2-the-sign-of-three-programme-guide | archive-date=3 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> get married. The episode takes place during the wedding reception and the story is told through flashbacks. The episode title is inspired by ''[[The Sign of the Four]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/04/10/love-interest-for-john-watson-in-new-sherlock-episode-the-sign-of-three-3591590/ | title=Love interest for John Watson in new Sherlock episode The Sign of Three? | publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | work=metro.co.uk | date=10 April 2013 | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207030556/http://metro.co.uk/2013/04/10/love-interest-for-john-watson-in-new-sherlock-episode-the-sign-of-three-3591590/ | archive-date=7 December 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> and was first broadcast on 5 January 2014.\n\nThe final episode \"[[His Last Vow]]\" was first broadcast on 12 January 2014, on [[BBC One]], and written by Steven Moffat, directed by [[Nick Hurran]] and is based on Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's \"[[The Adventure of Charles Augustus Milverton]]\". This case leads Sherlock into conflict with [[List of Sherlock characters#Charles Augustus Magnussen|Charles Augustus Magnussen]] ([[Lars Mikkelsen]]), a \"terrifying\" villain who was introduced as an unnamed villain in episode one. [[Mary Morstan]] and Sherlock Holmes both break into Magnussen's office, where, having surprised each other, Mary shoots Sherlock.  Later, Holmes deduces that Mary was formerly a [[Spy|secret agent]], and reveals this to Watson.  Holmes and Watson try to get Magnussen arrested, but their attempt fails, and Holmes shoots Magnussen to stop him from blackmailing Mary Watson. Mycroft arranges that Sherlock will be exiled from the United Kingdom instead of being tried for murder. As Sherlock's plane takes off, every video screen in London broadcasts the image of Moriarty, and Sherlock is recalled to deal with the crisis associated with Moriarty's potential return.\n\nThe third series aired in the United States on PBS over a period of three weeks, airing late January to early February 2014.\n\n=== Special (2016) ===\n[[File:Una Stubbs, filming Sherlock (2015).jpg|thumb|right|Stubbs pictured in costume for the episode, February 2015]]\n{{main|The Abominable Bride}}\nOn 2 July 2014, it was announced there would be a special episode broadcast between the third and fourth series. Filming began on 5 January 2015 and wrapped on 10 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/sherlock-miss-me|title=\"Miss me?\" The nation's favourite detective returns to BBC One|website=BBC Media Centre|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124170224/http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/sherlock-miss-me|archive-date=24 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/sherlock-special-begins-filming|title=Sherlock Special Begins Filming|website=Radio Times|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=13 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212084805/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/sherlock-special-begins-filming|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/drmuig/status/565245574564569088|title=Sherlock Special Filming Wrapped|website=Twitter|date=10 February 2015|accessdate=10 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305114238/https://twitter.com/drmuig/status/565245574564569088|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"S4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/sherlock-announcement-special-confirmed-three-3799440 |title=Sherlock announcement: Special confirmed with 'three new episodes' as #221back riddle is revealed |last=Hyland |first=Karen |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]] |date=2 July 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702224308/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/sherlock-announcement-special-confirmed-three-3799440 |archive-date=2 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat confirmed the episode is set in Victorian London, saying, \"The special is its own thing. We wouldn't have done the story we're doing, and the way we're doing it, if we didn't have this special. It's not part of the run of three episodes. So we had this to do it \u2026 It's kind of in its own little bubble.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/16/sherlock-special-victorian-|title=''Sherlock'' co-creator confirms special is set in Victorian London|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=16 March 2015|accessdate=18 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317234014/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/16/sherlock-special-victorian-|archive-date=17 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the title of the episode was announced. It was broadcast on 1 January 2016 at 9:00&nbsp;pm local time on BBC One in the UK, and on [[PBS]] in the US.<ref name=\"SpecialAirdate\" /> The episode was [[simulcast]] in British cinemas on 1 January, and was shown on 5 and 6 January 2016 in selected cinemas throughout the US.<ref>{{cite web| title=Sherlock: The Abominable Bride| url=http://www.fandango.com/sherlock:theabominablebride_188357/movieoverview| website=Fandango| publisher=NBCUniversal| accessdate=1 January 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101204957/http://www.fandango.com/sherlock:theabominablebride_188357/movieoverview| archive-date=1 January 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> Exclusive bonus material in the cinema presentation included a guided tour of 221B Baker Street from Steven Moffat and a look behind the scenes at how the special episode was made featuring all the lead cast and crew.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vue Cinemas |url=http://www.myvue.com/latest-movies/info/cinema/exeter/film/sherlock-the-abominable-bride |archive-url=https://archive.is/20160114094550/http://www.myvue.com/latest-movies/info/cinema/exeter/film/sherlock-the-abominable-bride |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 January 2016 |website=vue cinemas |accessdate=5 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 4 (2017) ===\nBy October 2013, a fourth series was commissioned, with scripts planned.<ref name=\"fourthseries\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/09/sherlock-back-fourth-series-steven-moffat |title=Sherlock will be back for fourth series, says producer Steven Moffat |last1=Brown |first1=Maggie |last2= |first2= |date=9 January 2014 |website=The Guardian Australia |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=11 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114215023/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/09/sherlock-back-fourth-series-steven-moffat |archive-date=14 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/sherlock-creators-reveal-already-series-6470060 | title= Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman commissioned Sherlock series 4 themselves says Steven Moffat | magazine= Radio Times | date= 14 October 2013 | accessdate= 7 January 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140107050844/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/sherlock-creators-reveal-already-series-6470060 | archive-date= 7 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat told [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Telegraph'']] in January 2014, \"we're all keen to continue\", but said it had been difficult to co-ordinate the lead actors' schedules.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sherlock creator denies plot holes in BBC drama |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10553570/Sherlock-creator-denies-plot-holes-in-BBC-drama.html |first1=Hayley |last1=Dixon |first2=Joe |last2=Kavanagh |date=6 January 2014 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=7 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107051843/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10553570/Sherlock-creator-denies-plot-holes-in-BBC-drama.html |archive-date=7 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming began on 4 April 2016 at [[Pinewood Studio Wales]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/sherlock-season-4-begins-filming-today|title='Sherlock' Series 4 begins filming!|work=CultBox|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=5 April 2016|last=Martin|first=William|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407014030/http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/sherlock-season-4-begins-filming-today|archive-date=7 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and lasted until 5 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/24/comic-con-2016-sherlock-panel|title=Comic-Con 2016: Sherlock panel reveals three key names to tease series 4|last=Smith|first=C. Molly|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=24 July 2016|accessdate=24 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725150922/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/24/comic-con-2016-sherlock-panel|archive-date=25 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BIvNCLGg1vx/ |title=It's a WRAP on #sherlock series IV 2016 |last=Caron|first=Benjamin|publisher=Instagram|date=5 August 2016|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> In May 2016 it was announced that [[Toby Jones]] had been cast as a villain from [[Sherlock Holmes]] lore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/Check-Out-Major-Villain-Sherlock-Season-4-138327.html|title=Check Out The Major Villain in Sherlock Series 4|last=Hurley|first=Laura|work=Cinemablend|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518232240/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/Check-Out-Major-Villain-Sherlock-Season-4-138327.html|archive-date=18 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth series premiered on 1 January 2017, with \"[[The Six Thatchers]]\".<ref name=\"S4Airdates\" /> The second episode \"[[The Lying Detective]]\" aired on 8 January 2017; the last episode \"[[The Final Problem (Sherlock)|The Final Problem]]\" aired on 15 January 2017.\n\n=== Future ===\nIn January 2014, Moffat stated that a fifth series had been plotted by himself and Gatiss;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/sherlock-writers-plot-fourth-and-fifth-series-9048981.html|title=Sherlock writers plot fourth and fifth series|last=Denham|first=Jess|work=The Independent|date=9 January 2014|accessdate=14 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809075954/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/sherlock-writers-plot-fourth-and-fifth-series-9048981.html|archive-date=9 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> however, by the release of the fourth series in January 2017, they had not yet decided whether to produce it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-15/mark-gatiss-and-steven-moffat-reveal-where-sherlock-could-go-in-series-5|title=Mark Gatiss and Steven Moffat reveal where Sherlock could go in series 5|last=Dowell|first=Ben|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116174355/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-15/mark-gatiss-and-steven-moffat-reveal-where-sherlock-could-go-in-series-5|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Cumberbatch and Moffat in particular have expressed interest in continuing at some point in the future, but there are no immediate plans.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jeffery|first1=Morgan|title=Sherlock series 5 air date, cast, episodes, news and everything you need to know|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/sherlock/feature/a819122/sherlock-season-5-air-date-cast-episodes-news-and-everything-you-need-to-know/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212013430/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/sherlock/feature/a819122/sherlock-season-5-air-date-cast-episodes-news-and-everything-you-need-to-know/|archive-date=12 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As to the future of the series, Gatiss stated that due to the conflicting schedules of Cumberbatch and Freeman, a potential fifth series is still up in the air.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|title=Steven Moffat speaks out on Sherlock's future: \"It rather depends on our two stars\"|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/cult/a819195/sherlock-series-5-steven-moffat-speaks-out-benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman/|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=17 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119120840/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/cult/a819195/sherlock-series-5-steven-moffat-speaks-out-benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; text-align:center; margin:10px\"\n|+ [[Metacritic]] ratings per series\n|-\n|{{Graph:Chart|width=200|height=100|yAxisMin=50|yAxisMax=100|x=Series 1, Series 2, Series3|y=85,91,88}}\n|-\n|<!-- begin inner table -->\n{| style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 1 (2010)|Series 1]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 2 (2012)|Series 2]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 3 (2014)|Series 3]]}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Rating\n| {{formatnum:85}}<ref name=MetacriticS1>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=30 November 2015 |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127200048/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=27 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:91}}<ref name=MetacriticS2>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 2 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=30 November 2015 |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120075203/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-2 |archive-date=20 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:88}}<ref name=MetacriticS3>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-3 |title=Sherlock: Series 3 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=2 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101024328/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-3 |archive-date=1 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- end inner table -->\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; text-align:center; margin:10px\"\n|+ [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ratings per series\n|-\n|{{Graph:Chart|width=200|height=100|yAxisMin=50|yAxisMax=100|x=Series 1, Series 2, Series 3, Series 4|y=93,94,91,56}}\n|-\n|<!-- begin inner table -->\n{| style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 1 (2010)|Series 1]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 2 (2012)|Series 2]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 3 (2014)|Series 3]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 4 (2017)|Series 4]]}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Rating\n| {{formatnum:93}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s01</ref>\n| {{formatnum:94}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s02</ref>\n| {{formatnum:91}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s03</ref>\n| {{formatnum:56}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s04</ref>\n|}\n<!-- end inner table -->\n|}\n\nThe show has received critical acclaim, sustaining positive reviews across its first three series. However, its fourth series received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherlock series 4: The most furiously outraged critics|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/sherlock-outraged-critical-reviews/|website=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129054352/https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/sherlock-outraged-critical-reviews/|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Shoemaker|first=Allison|title=The frustrating, brilliant Sherlock stays frustrating right to the end|url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-frustrating-brilliant-sherlock-stays-frustrating-r-1798190036|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129100046/https://tv.avclub.com/the-frustrating-brilliant-sherlock-stays-frustrating-r-1798190036|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Series one holds a [[Metacritic]] score of 85/100, based on 17 reviews, and series two scored 91/100, based on 24 reviews, while series three holds a score of 88/100, based on 22 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |title=Sherlock |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=21 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819095203/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=19 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first series holds a 93% rating at critical aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the second holds a 94% rating, and the third series has a 91% approval rating. The fourth series holds a rating of 56%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/ |title=Sherlock |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504191053/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=4 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first episode rated highly on the [[Appreciation Index]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a252133/sherlock-well-received-by-critics.html |title='Sherlock' well-received by critics |first=Paul |last=Millar |date=28 July 2010 |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=29 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69mEkNAkO?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a252133/sherlock-well-received-by-critics.html |archive-date=9 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Observer'' said the show was \"a cross between ''[[Withnail and I]]'' and ''[[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|The Bourne Ultimatum]]'', there is also a hint of ''Doctor Who'' about the drama; hardly surprising, since it has been written and created by ''Doctor Who'' writers Mark Gatiss and Steven Moffat.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock Holmes is back... sending texts and using nicotine patches |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/18/sherlock-holmes-is-back-bbc |work=The Observer |date=18 July 2010 |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030175252/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/18/sherlock-holmes-is-back-bbc |archive-date=30 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Dan Martin said, \"It's early days, but the first of three 90-minute movies, 'A Study in Pink', is brilliantly promising. It has the finesse of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' but is indisputably Sherlock Holmes. The deduction sequences are ingenious, and the plot is classic Moffat intricacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Sherlock makes Sunday night TV sexy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jul/23/sherlock-steven-moffat-mark-gatiss |work=The Guardian |date=23 July 2010 |accessdate=25 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8KTy31E?url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jul/23/sherlock-steven-moffat-mark-gatiss |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)|Tom Sutcliffe]] for ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote, \"''Sherlock'' is a triumph, witty and knowing, without ever undercutting the flair and dazzle of the original. It understands that Holmes isn't really about plot but about charisma ... Flagrantly unfaithful to the original in some respects, ''Sherlock'' is wonderfully loyal to it in every way that matters.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Sutcliffe |authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster) |title=The Weekend's TV: Sherlock, Sun, BBC1 Amish: World's Squarest Teenagers, Sun, Channel 4 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-tv-sherlock-sun-bbc1bramish-worlds-squarest-teenagers-sun-channel-4-2035302.html |work=The Independent |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=28 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8JbHRDe?url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-tv-sherlock-sun-bbc1bramish-worlds-squarest-teenagers-sun-channel-4-2035302.html |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lead actors were commended. Critic Victoria Thorpe said, \"Freeman's dependable, capable Watson unlocks this modern Holmes, a man who now describes himself as 'a high-functioning [[wikt:sociopathy|sociopath]]'.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Following the second series' opening episode, Sarah Crompton, for ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', asserts that \"Cumberbatch is utterly credible as a man who lives entirely in his cerebellum with little regard for the world outside, mak[ing] ''Sherlock'' the perfect depiction of Holmes for our times\".<ref name=\"crompton\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8987577/The-timeless-appeal-of-Holmess-sexy-logic.html|title=The timeless appeal of Holmes's sexy logic|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 January 2012|first=Sarah|last=Crompton|accessdate=5 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103041614/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8987577/The-timeless-appeal-of-Holmess-sexy-logic.html|archive-date=3 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> David Weigand of the ''[[SF Gate]]'' wrote, \"...a Sherlock for the 21st century.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/TV-review-Fresh-dose-of-fun-in-Sherlock-3248989.php|title=TV review: Fresh dose of fun in 'Sherlock'|last=Wiegand|first=David|date=2010-10-22|website=SFGate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> Jace Lacob of ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' wrote, \"Back from the dead and better than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jacelacob/sherlock-the-empty-hearse-season-3-review|title=\"Sherlock\" Is Back From The Dead And Better Than Ever|last=Lacob|first=Jace|date=2013-12-30|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\nConan Doyle fans were generally appreciative. Gwilym Mumford, for ''The Guardian'', suggested that \"this has to do with the fact that Moffat and Gatiss are enormously knowledgeable about Conan Doyle's work, and their reimagining incorporates big- and small-screen adaptations of Holmes, as well as the original stories. As Gatiss puts it: 'Everything is canonical.' \"<ref name=\"guard171211\">{{cite news |first=Gwilym |last=Mumford |title=Sherlock returns to the BBC: 'He's definitely devilish' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/dec/17/sherlock-bbc-cumberbatch-freeman-interview?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=19 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005124057/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/dec/17/sherlock-bbc-cumberbatch-freeman-interview?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sarah Crompton, for ''The Telegraph'', identifies some of the jokes and allusions intended for fans.<ref name=\"crompton\" /> Commenting specifically on the second series' finale \"The Reichenbach Fall\", ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Sam Wollaston praised the show's faithfulness to Conan Doyle, but also how \"it will wander, taking in mobile phone technology and computer hacking ... But it doesn't feel like cheating; more like an open relationship, agreed by both parties.\"<ref name=\"woll\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Sherlock/Call the Midwife/Hugh's Hungry Boys |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/15/tv-review-sherlock?newsfeed=true |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 January 2012 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011021611/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/15/tv-review-sherlock?newsfeed=true |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Sherlock'' was ranked 60th on ''The Guardian'''s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ratings ===\nAccording to overnight data provided by the [[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] (BARB), the highest overnight figure from the first series of ''Sherlock'' was 7.5&nbsp;million for the opening episode, \"A Study in Pink\", whereas the second series averaged over 8 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Marszal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9017545/Sherlock-finale-another-ratings-triumph.html |title=Sherlock finale another ratings triumph |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=16 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117104741/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9017545/Sherlock-finale-another-ratings-triumph.html |archive-date=17 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The three episodes of series two were the three most watched programmes on iPlayer, the BBC's video-on-demand service, between January and April 2012.<ref name=\"telegraph=iplayer\" /> Its opening episode, \"A Scandal in Belgravia\", attracted controversy from the tabloid newspaper ''[[Daily Mail]]'', which reported that Irene Adler's nude scene early in the episode had been met with disapproval from some viewers who were concerned that it had been shown before the 9:00&nbsp;pm [[Watershed (television)|watershed]] hour, before which adult-orientated content is not supposed to air.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC1's Sherlock: no mystery about the Mail's reaction |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2012/jan/03/bbc1-sherlock-mystery-mail |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=3 January 2012 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118072857/https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2012/jan/03/bbc1-sherlock-mystery-mail |archive-date=18 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"repeat\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock: BBC will not remove nude scenes for 7&nbsp;pm repeat |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/04/sherlock-bbc-nude-scenes?newsfeed=true |first=Tara |last=Conlan |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105160131/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/04/sherlock-bbc-nude-scenes?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some critics also took exception to Moffat's treatment of Irene Adler, arguing that she was sexualised,<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite news |title=Is Sherlock sexist? Steven Moffat's wanton women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/jan/03/sherlock-sexist-steven-moffat?newsfeed=true |first=Jane Clare |last=Jones |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105160115/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/jan/03/sherlock-sexist-steven-moffat?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> an argument rejected by others, including Moffat.<ref>{{cite web|first=Laura|last=Pledger|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-08/ten-strong-tv-women|title=Ten strong TV women|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=5 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420172628/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-08/ten-strong-tv-women|archive-date=20 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"missed-clue\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title='There is a clue everybody's missed': Sherlock writer Steven Moffat interviewed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211731/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series' conclusion, \"The Reichenbach Fall\", in which Sherlock fakes his suicide by jumping from St Bartholomew's Hospital, led to speculation on forums, social networking sites and in newspaper articles about its resolution.<ref name=\"missed-clue\" />\n\nThe third series became the UK's most watched drama series since 2001. An average 11.82&nbsp;million people watched the series, with about 12.72&nbsp;million tuning in for the first episode.<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\"/> The 2016 New Year's Day special drew 11.64&nbsp;million viewers. The fourth series opened with 11.3&nbsp;million viewers for the first episode, but dropped to 5.9&nbsp;million viewers by the final episode of the fourth series, the lowest overnight ever recorded by the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-16/sherlock-records-its-lowest-ever-overnight-audience-with-59m-tuning-into-series-four-finale/|title=Sherlock records its lowest ever overnight audience with 5.9m tuning into series four finale|last=Cowell|first=Ben|date=16 January 2017|work=Radio Times|accessdate=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117143919/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-16/sherlock-records-its-lowest-ever-overnight-audience-with-59m-tuning-into-series-four-finale|archive-date=17 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Sherlock}}\n\nIn the 2011 [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] awards, the show as a whole won the award for [[British Academy Television Award for Best Drama Series|Best Drama Series]], while Freeman (as Dr Watson) won the award for the [[British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. Cumberbatch was nominated for [[British Academy Television Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]. Andrew Scott won 2012's Best Supporting Actor, beating Freeman, for his work in the second series, which was nominated in other categories.<ref name=\"guard-bafta-2012\">{{cite news |first1=Vicky |last1=Frost |first2=John |last2=Plunkett |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/may/27/bafta-tv-awards-itv-fred-west-drama?newsfeed=true |title=Bafta TV acting awards won by stars of ITV Fred West drama |work=The Guardian |date=27 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306135120/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/may/27/bafta-tv-awards-itv-fred-west-drama?newsfeed=true |archive-date=6 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing multiple nominations for the [[63rd Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2011) and [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2012), the show won multiple Emmys at the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2014), including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Cumberbatch, [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Freeman and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special]] for Moffat. It subsequently won the Emmy for Best Television Film at the [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2016).\n\nThe first series also won the [[Arqiva]] award for the \"best terrestrial show\" at the 2011 Edinburgh International Television Festival.<ref>{{cite news |title=ITV1 named terrestrial channel of the year |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14700111 |work=BBC News |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=28 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828172013/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14700111 |archive-date=28 August 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"A Study in Pink\" and \"A Scandal in Belgravia\" were nominated for [[Emmy Award]]s in a variety of categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: A Study In Pink (Masterpiece) |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-study-pink-masterpiece |work=Emmys.com |accessdate=11 November 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I1yveRgh?url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-study-pink-masterpiece |archive-date=11 July 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"emmy2012\">{{cite web |title=Sherlock: A Scandal in Belgravia (Masterpiece) |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-scandal-belgravia-masterpiece |work=Emmys.com |accessdate=19 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721193933/http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-scandal-belgravia-masterpiece |archive-date=21 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series won several BAFTA Cymru awards: television drama, Director: Fiction (Euros Lyn), Director of Photography: Fiction (Steve Lawes), Production Design (Arwel Wyn Jones), and Make Up & Hair (Claire Pritchard-Jones).<ref name=\"harts=awards\">{{cite web|title=Sherlock Awards 2010/11 |url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/programmes/sherlock-awards-201011/ |work=Hartswood Films |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121218092737/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/programmes/sherlock-awards-201011/ |archivedate=18 December 2012 |df= }}</ref> Charlie Phillips won the 'Editing: Fiction' category at the [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref name=\"harts=awards\" /> The show was also nominated for the YouTube Audience Award.<ref>{{cite news |first1=John |last1=Plunkett |first2=Josh |last2=Halliday |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/22/sherlock-wins-best-drama-award-baftas |title=BBC's Sherlock wins best drama award at Baftas |date=22 May 2011 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=22 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930144021/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/22/sherlock-wins-best-drama-award-baftas |archive-date=30 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Home release and merchandise ==\n\n===DVD and Blu-ray release===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Series\n! colspan=\"3\" | DVD/Blu-ray release dates\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Additional features\n|-\n! Region 1/A\n! Region 2/B\n! Region 4/B\n|-\n! 1\n| 9 November 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-1-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004132HZS/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215204914/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-1-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004132HZS |archive-date=15 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 30 August 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-1-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B003TO5414/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111175754/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-1-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B003TO5414 |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 4 November 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-1/277108/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923123855/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-1/277108/ |archive-date=23 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Audio commentaries \"A Study in Pink\" and \"The Great Game\"\n* \"Unlocking Sherlock\" documentary<ref>{{cite web |title=Unlocking Sherlock |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV271627 |work=BBFC |date=2 August 2010 |accessdate=5 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119205846/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV271627 |archive-date=19 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Original pilot version of \"A Study in Pink\"<ref>''Sherlock'' DVD, Catalogue number: BBCDVD3223</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock DVD review |first=Stu |last=Anderson |work=Den of Geek |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/Reviews/581560/sherlock_dvd_review.html |date=1 September 2010 |accessdate=7 September 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67V3vBMlV?url=http://www.denofgeek.com/Reviews/581560/sherlock_dvd_review.html |archive-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| 22 May 2012<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 2 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-2-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004QOB8SO/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514184825/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-2-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004QOB8SO |archive-date=14 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 23 January 2012<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 2 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-2-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B005UL537Y/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730162535/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-2-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B005UL537Y |archive-date=30 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 1 March 2012<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 2 |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-2/294914/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111121717/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-2/294914/ |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Audio commentaries \"A Scandal in Belgravia\" and \"The Hounds of Baskerville\"\n* \"Sherlock Uncovered\" documentary<ref>{{cite web |title= Sherlock&nbsp;\u2013 the hounds of baskerville |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/BVV286085/ |work=British Board of Film Classification |date=20 December 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n! 3\n| 11 February 2014<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 3 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-3-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B00E3UN44W/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928164547/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-3-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B00E3UN44W |archive-date=28 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 20 January 2014<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 3 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-3-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B00DRDCIA2/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111175713/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-3-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B00DRDCIA2 |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 20 February 2014<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 3 |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-3/526289/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111121655/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-3/526289/ |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Featurettes: \"The Fall\", \"Fans, Villains, and Speculation: The Legacy of Sherlock Holmes\", and \"Shooting Sherlock\"\n|-\n! Special\n| 12 January 2016<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: The Abominable Bride |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Abominable-Bride-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B013JBJ7EG/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107162013/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Abominable-Bride-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B013JBJ7EG |archive-date=7 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 11 January 2016<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: The Abominable Bride |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-Abominable-Bride-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B0119OFSGQ/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923052351/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-Abominable-Bride-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B0119OFSGQ |archive-date=23 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 3 February 2016<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: The Abominable Bride |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-the-abominable-bride/889149/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111121700/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-the-abominable-bride/889149/ |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* A Study in ''Sherlock'': \"Making of\" production documentary\n* Behind-the-scenes, interviews with Moffat and Gatiss\n* ''Sherlock''ology Q&A\n|-\n! 4\n| 24 January 2017<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 4 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-Four-Various/dp/B01K5HWFNM/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916061839/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-Four-Various/dp/B01K5HWFNM |archive-date=16 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 23 January 2017<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 4 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-4-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B01IRDD4ZY/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207102850/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-4-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B01IRDD4ZY |archive-date=7 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 15 February 2017<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 4 |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-4/333191/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111121705/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-4/333191/ |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Featurettes: \"Behind 221B\", \"Script to Screen\", \"The Writers Chat\", \"Production Diary\", \"221B Set Timelapse\"\n* The Set Tour, with Mark Gatiss\n|}\n\n===Books and websites===\n\n[[BBC Books]] published some of Conan Doyle's original collections and novels as [[tie-in]] editions, with [[cover art]] featuring Cumberbatch and Freeman. ''A Study in Scarlet'' and ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' were released in autumn 2011, with introductions by Moffat and Gatiss respectively.<ref name=\"moff-study\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Sherlock&nbsp;\u2013 [[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]] |first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |year=2011 |publisher=BBC Books |isbn=1-84990-367-0 |origyear=First published 1892}}</ref> ''The Hound of the Baskervilles'', ''The Sign of Four'' and ''[[The Memoirs of Sherlock Holmes]]'' were released in March 2012, with introductions by Cumberbatch, Freeman and Thompson respectively.<ref name=\"memoirs\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Sherlock&nbsp;\u2013 [[The Hound of the Baskervilles]] |first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher=BBC Books |year=2012 |origyear=First published 1902|isbn=1-84990-409-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Sherlock&nbsp;\u2013 [[The Sign of the Four|Sign of Four]] |first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher=BBC Books |year=2012 |isbn=1-84990-404-9|origyear=First published 1890}}</ref> Two more books, ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[His Last Bow]]'', were released in December 2013, ahead of the premiere of the third series. They featured introductions by Gatiss and Moffat respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherlockology.com/news/2013/11/18/new-sherlock-books-181113 |title=New Sherlock tie-in books coming soon! |publisher=Sherlockology |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=6 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131120030237/http://www.sherlockology.com/news/2013/11/18/new-sherlock-books-181113 |archive-date=20 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Radio Times]]'', the popularity of ''Sherlock'' has led to a resurgence in the sales of the original Conan Doyle stories.<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Jones |title=Benedict Cumberbatch's Sherlock boosts Conan Doyle book sales |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-01-17/benedict-cumberbatch%27s-sherlock-boosts-conan-doyle-book-sales |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118102747/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-01-17/benedict-cumberbatch's-sherlock-boosts-conan-doyle-book-sales |archive-date=18 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Publishers and retailers reported a 180% rise in sales of Sherlock Holmes books during the first series' broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stone |first1= Philip|first2= Katie |last2=Allen|date=12 August 2010 |archivedate=15 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815050142/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/125685-no-shit-sherlock-as-tv-adaptation-boosts-book-sales.html |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/125685-no-shit-sherlock-as-tv-adaptation-boosts-book-sales.html|title= No shit Sherlock as TV adaptation boosts book sales|publisher= TheBookseller.com|accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Sherlock: The Casebook'', a companion book to the series written by [[Guy Adams]], was published by BBC Books in the United Kingdom in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock The Casebook revealed |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-08-14/sherlock-the-casebook-revealed |first=Paul |last=Jones |date=14 August 2012 |work=Radio Times |accessdate=16 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815233412/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-08-14/sherlock-the-casebook-revealed |archive-date=15 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"casebook\">[[Guy Adams|Adams, Guy]], ''Sherlock: The Casebook'', BBC Books, 25 October 2012, {{ISBN|978-1849904254}}</ref> The book was republished in the United States under the title ''The Sherlock Files: The Official Companion to the Hit Television Series'' in July 2013.<ref name=\"companion\">{{Cite book |authorlink=Guy Adams |last=Adams |first=Guy |title=The Sherlock Files: The Official Companion to the Hit Television Series |publisher=It Books |date=16 July 2013 |isbn=978-0-06227-809-8}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, a [[manga]] adaptation of the series illustrated by Jay was serialised in [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]'s ''[[Young Ace]]'' magazine from 4 October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-09-01/bbc-tv-sherlock-re-imagining-gets-japanese-manga |title=BBC TV's Sherlock Re-imagining Gets Japanese Manga&nbsp;\u2013 News |publisher=Anime News Network |date=1 September 2012 |accessdate=30 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005070036/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-09-01/bbc-tv-sherlock-re-imagining-gets-japanese-manga |archive-date=5 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The English translation of this manga series will be released by [[Titan Books|Titan Comics]] in the UK and US beginning on 8 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/03/21/sherlock-manga-gets-alternate-covers-and-western-release-date/#77efce281958|title='Sherlock' Manga Gets Alternate Covers And Western Release Date|first=Ollie|last=Barder|date=21 March 2016|work=Forbes|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019004959/https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/03/21/sherlock-manga-gets-alternate-covers-and-western-release-date/#77efce281958|archive-date=19 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2012, [[Winning Moves]] sold a Sherlock-themed edition of [[Cluedo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/worldwide/sherlock-cluedo.html |title=Media Centre&nbsp;\u2013 Sherlock fans can play detective with new Sherlock Cluedo |publisher=BBC |date=25 September 2012 |accessdate=30 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928042145/http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/worldwide/sherlock-cluedo.html |archive-date=28 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[BBC Online]] published several tie-in websites relating to the show's fictional world. These were written by [[Joseph Lidster]], who had also contributed to the ''Doctor Who'' tie-in websites.<ref name=\"tieien\">{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Other Sherlock related websites |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/sherlock/disclaimer.shtml |work=BBC Online |accessdate=25 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727143507/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/sherlock/disclaimer.shtml |archive-date=27 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nTwo websites \u2013 thescienceofdeduction.co.uk and johnwatsonblog.co.uk \u2013 feature the events from the show in the form of puzzles and case-summaries, often with comments (for example, by John Watson's sister, \"Harry\"). There are also several blogs about \"unseen\" cases that do not feature on television. Similar to the broadcast cases, these retain familiar elements from classic Arthur Conan Doyle stories: \"The Geek Interpreter\" instead of \"[[The Adventure of the Greek Interpreter|The Greek Interpreter]]\", and \"The Six Thatchers\" instead of \"The Six Napoleons\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnwatsonblog.co.uk/blog/19december|title=The blog of Dr. John. H. Watson|work=johnwatsonblog.co.uk|access-date=3 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804115726/http://www.johnwatsonblog.co.uk/blog/19december|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On the websites, links can be found to Molly Hooper's diary and the official website of Connie Prince.\n\n===Clothing===\nThe show's popularity resulted in enquiries for coats similar to Sherlock's, reported retailer [[Debenhams]]. Garment manufacturer Belstaff put the wool trench coat worn by Benedict Cumberbatch back into production before the series had ended.<ref name=\"petridis\">{{cite news |first=Alexis |last=Petridis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis |title=No chic, Sherlock |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/sep/04/sherlock-fashion-mens-coats |date=4 September 2010 |accessdate=7 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105160141/http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/sep/04/sherlock-fashion-mens-coats |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Independent'' reported, \"designer [[Paul Costelloe]] moved to meet the demand, offering tailored coats and scarves based on the series, while [[Savile Row]] bespoke tailor John Pearse said many of his clients were inquiring about the actors' clothes.\"<ref name=\"indep-costume\" /> Journalist [[Alexis Petridis]] commented, \"[Y]ou can see why men wanted to get the look. Perhaps they noted the effect Cumberbatch, by no means your standard telly hunk, had on lady viewers [\u2026] and decided it must have something to do with the clobber. So it is that Britain's latest men's style icon is a fictional [[asexuality|asexual]] sociopath first seen onscreen hitting a corpse with a horse whip. Surely not even the great detective himself could have deduced that was going to happen.\"<ref name=\"petridis\" />\n\n===Games===\n\nIn January 2014, the show launched its official [[mobile app]]  ''Sherlock: The Network'', which was created by The Project Factory in association with Hartswood Films. Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman appear in cameo roles as Holmes and Dr Watson, respectively.<ref name=\"Jeffrey\"/><ref name=\"itunes.apple.com\"/>\n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that a live ''Sherlock'' experience, ''[[Sherlock: The Game Is Now]]'', would be opening in London in October 2018. The experience was written by Moffat and Gatiss, and would feature audio and video scenes with \"original ''Sherlock'' cast members\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/06/06/steven-moffats-secret-sherlock-project-game-now-revealed-escape/|title=Steven Moffat's 'secret' Sherlock project The Game is Now revealed to be an escape room|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=6 June 2018|accessdate=22 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823005918/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/06/06/steven-moffats-secret-sherlock-project-game-now-revealed-escape/|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The experience, which is built in the [[West 12|West 12 shopping centre]] in [[Shepherd's Bush]] and designed by the [[escape room]] creators of London's ''Time Run'',<ref name=\"standard\">{{cite news|last=Edmonds|first=Lizzie|title=Sherlock: The Game Is Now \u2013 First look inside new immersive escape room in Shepherd's Bush|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/attractions/sherlock-holmes-game-is-now-immersive-game-london-a4003301.html|work=[[Evening Standard]]|date=29 November 2018|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207060600/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/attractions/sherlock-holmes-game-is-now-immersive-game-london-a4003301.html|archive-date=7 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> begins in [[221B Baker Street]] and requires teams to solve mysteries to progress along through the 60-minute game.<ref name=\"standard\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote|Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock}}\n{{commons category|Sherlock (TV series)}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120119041032/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/Sherlock-Series-1-program.aspx ''Sherlock'' series 1] at [[Hartswood Films]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120111070446/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/Sherlock-Series-2-program.aspx ''Sherlock'' series 2] at Hartswood Films\n* {{IMDb title|1475582}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/shows/sherlock/ ''Sherlock''] at [[TV.com]]\n* [http://www.tvguide.co.uk/titlesearch.asp?title=sherlock ''Sherlock''] at ''[[TV Guide]]''\n\n{{Sherlock}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sherlock|Awards for ''Sherlock'']]\n|list  = \n{{BAFTA TV Award for Best Drama Series 2010\u20132029}}\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Miniseries}}\n{{EmmyAward TelevisionMovie}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Miniseries or Television Film}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Movies, Miniseries and Specials}}\n}}\n{{Sherlock Holmes screen adaptations}}\n{{Steven Moffat}}\n{{Media in Cardiff}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United Kingdom|BBC|Law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherlock (TV series)}}\n[[Category:2010 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British crime television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British mystery television series]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (television series)]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:British crime television series]]\n[[Category:British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning television programs]]\n[[Category:Sherlock (TV series)|*]]\n[[Category:Sherlock Holmes films based on works by Arthur Conan Doyle]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on novels]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hartswood Films]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British crime drama television series, first broadcast in 2010}}\n{{For|other series about Sherlock Holmes|Sherlock Holmes (disambiguation)#Television}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Sherlock\n| image                    = Sherlock titlecard.jpg\n| alt                      = A view of the London skyline, with the word \"Sherlock\" in black letters\n| caption                  = Title card\n| genre                    = [[Crime film|Crime]]\n| creator                  = {{Plain list|\n* [[Mark Gatiss]]\n* [[Steven Moffat]]}}\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Canon of Sherlock Holmes|Sherlock Holmes]]''|[[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]}}\n| writer                   = {{Plain list|\n* Mark Gatiss\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]]}}\n| starring                 = {{Plain list|\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]]\n* [[Martin Freeman]]\n* [[Rupert Graves]]\n* [[Una Stubbs]]\n* Mark Gatiss\n* [[Louise Brealey]]\n* [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]]\n* [[Amanda Abbington]]\n}}\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David Arnold]]\n* [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]]\n}}\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 4\n| num_episodes             = 13\n| list_episodes            = List of Sherlock episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Mark Gatiss\n* Steven Moffat\n* [[Beryl Vertue]]\n* [[Rebecca Eaton]]\n* Bethan Jones\n* [[Sue Vertue]]\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Unbulleted list|Sue Vertue|Elaine Cameron }}\n| editor                   = {{Unbulleted list|Charlie Phillips|Mali Evans|[[Tim Porter]]|Yan Miles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/news/2015/sherlock-editor-yan-miles-wins-an-eddie-award/|title=Sherlock editor Yan Miles wins an Eddie Award|website=Hartswood Films|access-date=3 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104074906/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/news/2015/sherlock-editor-yan-miles-wins-an-eddie-award/|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| cinematography           = {{Unbulleted list|[[Fabian Wagner]]|Steve Lawes}}\n| camera                   = Single camera\n| runtime                  = 85\u201390 minutes\n| company                  = {{Unbulleted list|[[Hartswood Films]]|[[BBC Cymru Wales|BBC Wales]]|[[WGBH-TV|WGBH]]}}\n| channel                  = {{Unbulleted list|[[BBC One]]|[[BBC HD]] (2010)|[[BBC One HD]] (2012\u2013present) |[[PBS]] (2010\u2013present)}}\n| picture_format           = [[576i50]]<br />[[1080i50]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|7|25|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2017|1|15|df=y}}<!-- Per the documentation at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_television, for the \"last_aired\" parameter: \"In some cases the fate of a program might be uncertain, for example if there are no announcements that a show has been renewed. If such a program has not aired a new episode in 12 months, \"present\" can be changed to the date the last episode aired, using {{End date}}. This does not imply the series has been cancelled, rather that the program \"last aired\" on that date. This is to prevent programs from being listed as \"present\" in perpetuity.\" -->\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws\n| production_website       = https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/sherlock/\n| production_website_title = PBS Official Website\n}}\n'''''Sherlock''''' is a British [[Crime film|crime]] television series based on [[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]'s [[Sherlock Holmes]] detective stories. Created by [[Steven Moffat]] and [[Mark Gatiss]], it stars [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] as Sherlock Holmes and [[Martin Freeman]] as [[Dr. Watson|Doctor John Watson]]. 13 episodes have been produced, with four three-part series airing from 2010 to 2017, and a special episode that aired on 1 January 2016. The series is set in the present day, while the one-off special features a Victorian period fantasy resembling the original Holmes stories. ''Sherlock'' is produced by the British network [[BBC]], along with [[Hartswood Films]], with Moffat, Gatiss, [[Sue Vertue]] and [[Rebecca Eaton]] serving as executive producers. The series is supported by the American station [[WGBH-TV]] Boston for its ''[[Masterpiece (TV series)|Masterpiece]]'' [[anthology series]] on [[PBS]], where it also airs in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/about/blogs/news/masterpiece-and-pbs-announce-new-sherlock-special-to-premiere-on-january-1/|title=MASTERPIECE and PBS Announce New \"Sherlock\" Special to Premiere on January 1|work=PBS|date=25 October 2015|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703001255/http://www.pbs.org/about/blogs/news/masterpiece-and-pbs-announce-new-sherlock-special-to-premiere-on-january-1|archive-date=3 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/pbs-bbc-co-production-deal-1201408869/|title=PBS & BBC Ink Multi-Title Co-Production Deal|work=Variety|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818001325/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/pbs-bbc-co-production-deal-1201408869/|archive-date=18 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/bbc-pbs-renew-masterpiece-partnership-14482/|title=BBC, PBS Renew 'Masterpiece' Partnership|work=The Wrap|date=22 February 2010|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019233657/http://www.thewrap.com/bbc-pbs-renew-masterpiece-partnership-14482/|archive-date=19 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The series is primarily filmed in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], with [[Gower Street, London|North Gower Street]] in [[London]] used for exterior shots of Holmes and Watson's [[221B Baker Street]] residence.\n\n''Sherlock'' has been praised for the quality of its writing, acting, and direction. It has been [[List of awards and nominations received by Sherlock|nominated for numerous awards]] including [[Emmy Award|Emmys]], [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTAs]] and a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]], winning several awards across a variety of categories. The show won in three categories at the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Cumberbatch, [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Freeman and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Outstanding Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special]] for Moffat. Two years later, it won [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]]. In addition, the show was also honoured with a [[Peabody Award]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/masterpiece-sherlock-a-study-in-pink |title=Masterpiece: Sherlock: A Study in Pink (PBS) |website=Peabody Awards |date=May 2011 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8KuuOqD?url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/masterpiece-sherlock-a-study-in-pink |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series became the UK's most watched drama series since 2001.<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-22/sherlock-is-most-watched-drama-series-for-over-a-decade|title=Sherlock series 3 is most watched BBC drama series for over a decade. An average of almost 12 million people tuned into the third series of the detective drama on BBC1|last=Jones|first=Paul|work=Radio Times|date=22 January 2014}}</ref> ''Sherlock'' has been sold to 180 territories.<ref name=\"S5Lang\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jNzeuzYPiLc|title=Sherlock in five languages \u2013 BBC Worldwide Showcase|date=23 February 2012|work=YouTube|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502012133/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jNzeuzYPiLc|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll of the series have been released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]], alongside [[tie-in]] editions of selected original Conan Doyle stories and an original soundtrack composed by [[David Arnold]] and [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]]. In January 2014, the show launched its official [[mobile app]] called ''Sherlock: The Network''.<ref name=\"Jeffrey\">{{cite web|last=Jeffrey|first=Morgan|title=Sherlock: The Network app: 'It's a bit of Cumberbatch in your pocket'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tech/s129/sherlock/news/a545410/sherlock-the-network-app-its-a-bit-of-cumberbatch-in-your-pocket.html|publisher=Digital Spy|access-date=22 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122054400/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tech/s129/sherlock/news/a545410/sherlock-the-network-app-its-a-bit-of-cumberbatch-in-your-pocket.html|archive-date=22 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"itunes.apple.com\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/sherlock-the-network/id734800854?mt=8|title=Sherlock: The Network. Official App of the hit TV detective series|author=The Digital Development Factory Pty Ltd|date=20 January 2014|work=App Store|access-date=22 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305100822/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/sherlock-the-network/id734800854?mt=8|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Premise ==\n''Sherlock'' depicts \"consulting detective\" [[Sherlock Holmes]] ([[Benedict Cumberbatch]]) solving various mysteries in modern-day London. Holmes is assisted by his [[roommate|flatmate]] and friend, [[Dr. Watson|Dr. John Watson]] ([[Martin Freeman]]), who has returned from [[Operation Herrick|military service in Afghanistan]] with the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]. Although [[Metropolitan Police Service]] [[Inspector Lestrade|Detective Inspector Greg Lestrade]] ([[Rupert Graves]]) and others are suspicious of Holmes at first, over time, his exceptional intellect and bold powers of observation persuade them of his value. In part through Watson's [[blog]] documenting their adventures, Holmes becomes a reluctant celebrity with the press reporting on his cases and eccentric personal life. Both ordinary people and the British government ask for his help.\n\nAlthough the series depicts a variety of crimes and perpetrators, Holmes' conflict with [[Archenemy|nemesis]] [[Professor Moriarty|Jim Moriarty]] ([[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]]) is a recurring feature. [[List of Sherlock characters|Molly Hooper]] ([[Louise Brealey]]), a [[Pathology|pathologist]] at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital|St. Bart's Hospital]], occasionally assists Holmes in his cases. Other recurring roles include [[Una Stubbs]] as [[Minor Sherlock Holmes characters|Mrs. Hudson]], Holmes and Watson's landlady, and series co-creator [[Mark Gatiss]] as Holmes' elder brother [[Mycroft Holmes|Mycroft]].\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Conception and development ===\nSteven Moffat and Mark Gatiss, Sherlock Holmes fans with experience of adapting or using [[Victorian literature]] for television, devised the concept of the series.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /><ref name= \"Parker\">{{cite news |last= Parker |first= Robin |date= 23 August 2008 |url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/08/doctor_whos_moffat_to_pen_modern_sherlock_holmes.html |title= Doctor Who's Moffat to pen modern Sherlock Holmes |format= subscription access |work= [[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]] |publisher= Emap Media |accessdate= 27 December 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081202221914/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/08/doctor_whos_moffat_to_pen_modern_sherlock_holmes.html |archive-date= 2 December 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat had previously adapted the ''[[Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde]]'' for the 2007 series ''[[Jekyll (TV series)|Jekyll]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Walton |title=The weekend on television |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/06/18/nosplit/bvtv18last.xml |work=The Telegraph |date=18 June 2007 |accessdate=28 July 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021215855/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2007%2F06%2F18%2Fnosplit%2Fbvtv18last.xml |archive-date=21 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> while Gatiss had written the [[Charles Dickens|Dickensian]] ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[The Unquiet Dead]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Gatiss |first = Mark |authorlink=Mark Gatiss |title=Doctor Who: The Shooting Scripts | publisher=[[BBC Books]] |year=2005 |isbn=0-563-48641-4}}</ref> Moffat and Gatiss, both ''Doctor Who'' writers, discussed plans for a Holmes adaptation during their numerous train journeys to [[Cardiff]] where ''Doctor Who'' production is based.<ref>{{cite news|last= Bevan|first= Nathan|date= 15 January 2009|url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/01/15/benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman-star-in-new-bbc-sherlock-holmes-drama-filmed-in-cardiff-91466-22695776/|title= Benedict Cumberbatch, Martin Freeman star in new BBC Sherlock Holmes drama filmed in Cardiff|work= South Wales Echo|publisher= Western Mail and Echo|access-date= 26 July 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100315154446/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/01/15/benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman-star-in-new-bbc-sherlock-holmes-drama-filmed-in-cardiff-91466-22695776/|archive-date= 15 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> While they were in [[Monte Carlo]] for an awards ceremony, producer [[Sue Vertue]], who is married to Moffat, encouraged Moffat and Gatiss to develop the project themselves before another creative team had the same idea.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\">Sue Vertue, Steven Moffat and Mark Gatiss. DVD audio commentary for \"A Study in Pink\"</ref> Moffat and Gatiss invited Stephen Thompson to write for the series in September 2008.<ref name=\"memoirs\">Thompson, Steve \"Introduction\" In: {{cite book | series =Sherlock | title = [[The Memoirs of Sherlock Holmes]] |first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher = BBC Books | year=2012 |isbn=1-84990-406-5|origyear= 1894 |pages = vii\u2013ix}}</ref>\n\nGatiss has criticised recent television adaptations of the Conan Doyle stories as \"too reverential and too slow\", aiming instead to be as irreverent to the [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] as the [[Sherlock Holmes (1939 film series)|1930s and 1940s films]] starring [[Basil Rathbone]] and [[Nigel Bruce]], which were mostly set in the then-contemporary [[interwar]] era.<ref name = \"thorpe\" /> Benedict Cumberbatch's Sherlock uses modern technology, such as texting, the internet and [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] to solve crimes.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> [[Paul McGuigan (filmmaker)|Paul McGuigan]], who directed two episodes of ''Sherlock'', says that this is in keeping with Conan Doyle's character, pointing out that \"[i]n the books he would use any device possible and he was always in the lab doing experiments. It's just a modern day version of it. He will use the tools that are available to him today in order to find things out.\"<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news |title=Times have changed but crimes are the same for new Sherlock Holmes |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/times-have-changed-but-crimes-are-the-same-for-new-sherlock-holmes-1.1042129 |first=Brian |last=Pendreigh |date=19 July 2010 |work=The Herald |accessdate=20 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67V3OiHY4?url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/times-have-changed-but-crimes-are-the-same-for-new-sherlock-holmes-1.1042129 |archive-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe update maintains various elements of the original stories, such as the [[221B Baker Street|Baker Street address]] and Holmes' adversary Moriarty.<ref name=\"telegraph19122008\" /> Some of these elements are transposed to the present day: for example, Martin Freeman's Watson has returned from [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|military service in Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news| agency = AP| date = 16 August 2009| url = http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/2009/08/16/life-outside-the-office-for-martin-freeman-91466-24449418/| title = Life outside The Office for Martin Freeman| work = Wales on Sunday| publisher = Western Mail and Echo| access-date = 24 August 2009| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120118193611/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/2009/08/16/life-outside-the-office-for-martin-freeman-91466-24449418/| archive-date = 18 January 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> While discussing the fact that the original Watson was invalided home after serving in the [[Second Anglo-Afghan War]] (1878\u201380), Gatiss realised that \"[i]t is the same war now, I thought. The same unwinnable war.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" />\n\n''Sherlock'' was announced as a single 60-minute drama production at the [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]] in August 2008, with broadcast set for mid- to late 2009.<ref name = \"telegraph19122008\" /> The intention was to produce a series of six 60-minute episodes should the pilot prove to be successful.<ref name = \"s1ep1-comm\" /><ref name=\"telegraph19122008\">{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3852882/BBC-to-make-a-modern-day-Sherlock-Holmes.html |title= BBC to make a modern-day Sherlock Holmes |date= 19 December 2008 |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate= 20 July 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100315161707/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3852882/BBC-to-make-a-modern-day-Sherlock-Holmes.html |archive-date= 15 March 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first version of the pilot\u2014reported by ''[[The Guardian]]'' to have cost \u00a3800,000\u2014led to rumours within the BBC and wider media that ''Sherlock'' was a potential disaster.<ref name = \"Mail-yearend\" /><ref name =\"lawson-rebirth\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Lawson |authorlink=Mark Lawson |title=The rebirth of Sherlock |date=2 September 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/sep/02/sherlock-mark-lawson |work=The Guardian |accessdate=7 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002154049/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/sep/02/sherlock-mark-lawson |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The BBC decided not to transmit the pilot, requesting a reshoot and a total of three 90-minute episodes.<ref name=\"Mail-yearend\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/dec/26/christmas-tv-replay-2010-downloads|title=Replay the best of 2010|last=Heritage|first=Stuart|date=24 December 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=18 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002165217/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/dec/26/christmas-tv-replay-2010-downloads|archive-date=2 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name= \"lawson-rebirth\" /> The original pilot was included on the DVD of the first series. During the audio commentary, the creative team said that the BBC were \"very happy\" with the pilot but asked them to change the format.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Critic [[Mark Lawson]] observes that the pilot that was on air was \"substantially expanded and rewritten, and completely reimagined in look, pace and sound\".<ref name=\"lawson-rebirth\" /> In July 2009, the BBC drama department announced plans for three 90-minute episodes, to be broadcast in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last= McMahon |first= Kate |date= 14 July 2009 |url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc1-unveils-new-dramas/5003543.article |title= BBC1 unveils new dramas |format= subscription access |work= Broadcast |publisher= Emap Media |accessdate= 21 July 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090721013719/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc1-unveils-new-dramas/5003543.article |archive-date= 21 July 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat had previously announced that if a series of ''Sherlock'' was commissioned, Gatiss would take over the duties of executive producer so that he could concentrate on producing ''Doctor Who''.<ref name=\"Parker\" />\n\n=== Cast and characters ===\n{{Main|List of Sherlock characters}}\nMoffat and Vertue became interested in casting Cumberbatch as the title character after watching his performance in the 2007 film ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]''. The actor was cast after [[Audition|reading the script]] for the creative team.<ref name=\"unlocking\">\"Unlocking Sherlock\", documentary included on the Series 1 DVD/Blu-Ray release</ref> \"Cumberbatch\", says ''The Guardian'', \"has a reputation for playing odd, brilliant men very well, and his Holmes is cold, techie, slightly [[Asperger syndrome|Aspergerish]]\".<ref name=\"Mitchison\">{{cite news |first=Amanda |last=Mitchison |title=Benedict Cumberbatch on playing Sherlock Holmes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/17/benedict-cumberbatch-sherlock-holmes |work=The Guardian |date=17 July 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930144744/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/17/benedict-cumberbatch-sherlock-holmes |archive-date=30 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cumberbatch said, \"There's a great charge you get from playing him, because of the volume of words in your head and the speed of thought\u2014you really have to make your connections incredibly fast. He is one step ahead of the audience and of anyone around him with normal intellect. They can't quite fathom where his leaps are taking him.\"<ref name=\"Mitchison\" /> [[Piers Wenger]], head of drama at [[BBC Cymru Wales]], described the series' rendering of Sherlock as \"a dynamic [[superhero]] in a modern world, an arrogant, genius sleuth driven by a desire to prove himself cleverer than the perpetrator and the police\u2014everyone in fact\".<ref name=\"telegraph19122008\" /> Addressing changing social attitudes and broadcasting regulations, Cumberbatch's Holmes replaced the [[Pipe smoking|pipe]] with multiple [[nicotine patch]]es.<ref name=\"herald\" /> The writers believed that Sherlock should not talk like \"a completely modern person\", says Moffat, but were initially intent that \"he never sounded like he's giving a lecture\". Moffat turned the character \"more Victorian\" in the second series, capitalising more on Cumberbatch's \"beautiful voice\" to make it sound like \"he's giving a lecture\".<ref name=\"ds-moff-trf\">{{cite web |title='Sherlock' Steven Moffat interview: 'Holmes might not survive' |date=11 January 2012 |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a359357/sherlock-steven-moffat-interview-holmes-might-not-survive.html |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=13 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113013556/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a359357/sherlock-steven-moffat-interview-holmes-might-not-survive.html |archive-date=13 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{multiple image|total_width=320|image1=Benedict Cumberbatch filming Sherlock cropped2.jpg|image2=Martin Freeman filming Sherlock cropped2.jpg|footer=[[Benedict Cumberbatch]] (left) and [[Martin Freeman]] (right) during filming of the first series}}\nIn an interview with ''[[The Observer]]'', co-creator Mark Gatiss says that they experienced more difficulty finding the right actor to play [[Dr. Watson|Dr. John Watson]] than they had for the title character.<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Producer Sue Vertue said, \"Benedict was the only person we actually saw for [the part of] Sherlock... Once Benedict was there it was really just making sure we got the chemistry for John [Watson]\u2014and I think you get it as soon as they come into the room, you can see that they work together\".<ref name=\"guard-renew\" /> Several actors auditioned for the part of Watson,<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> and Martin Freeman eventually took the role. Steven Moffat said that [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] was the first to audition unsuccessfully. He was rejected for being too \"barmy\", as the producers required someone \"straighter\" for Watson.<ref name=\"mattsmith\">{{cite news|last=French|first=Dan|date=4 February 2010|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctorwho/news/a201372/matt-smith-rejected-for-bbcs-sherlock.html|title=Matt Smith rejected for BBC's 'Sherlock'|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=4 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100207081631/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctorwho/news/a201372/matt-smith-rejected-for-bbcs-sherlock.html|archive-date=7 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after, Moffat cast Smith as the [[Eleventh Doctor]] in ''Doctor Who''.<ref name=\"mattsmith\" />\n\nThe writers said that Freeman's casting developed the way in which Cumberbatch played Holmes.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> The theme of friendship appealed to both Gatiss and Moffat.<ref name=\"moff-study\">Moffat, Steven \"Introduction\" In: {{cite book |title=Sherlock: A Study in Scarlet|first=Arthur |last=Conan Doyle |publisher=Random House |year=2011|pages=xi\u2013xii |isbn=1-84990-366-2}}</ref> Gatiss asserted the importance of achieving the correct tone for the character. \"Watson is not an idiot, although it's true that Conan Doyle always took the piss out of him,\" said Gatiss. \"But only an idiot would surround himself with idiots.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Moffat said that Freeman is \"the sort of opposite of Benedict in everything except the amount of talent... Martin finds a sort of poetry in the ordinary man. I love the fastidious realism of everything he does.\"<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Freeman describes his character as a \"moral compass\" for Sherlock, who does not always consider the morality and ethics of his actions.<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\nRupert Graves was cast as DI Greg Lestrade. The writers referred to the character as \"Inspector Lestrade\" during development until Gatiss realised that in contemporary England the character would have the title \"Detective Inspector\". Moffat and Gatiss pointed out that Lestrade does not appear often in the stories and is quite inconsistently portrayed in them. They decided to go with the version that appeared in \"[[The Adventure of the Six Napoleons]]\": a man who is frustrated by Holmes but admires him, and whom Holmes considers as the best person at [[Scotland Yard]].<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> Several candidates took a comedic tack in their auditions, but the creative team preferred the gravitas that Graves brought to the role.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> His first name is revealed to be Greg in \"The Hounds of Baskerville\".<ref name=\"s2ep2\">{{cite episode |title=The Hounds of Baskerville |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Mark Gatiss, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=8 January 2012 |seriesno=2 |number=2}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Scott made his first appearance as Jim Moriarty in \"The Great Game\". Moffat said, \"We knew what we wanted to do with Moriarty from the very beginning. Moriarty is usually a rather dull, rather posh villain so we thought someone who was genuinely properly frightening. Someone who's an absolute psycho.\"<ref name=\"guard-renew\" /> Moffat and Gatiss were originally not going to put a confrontation between Moriarty and Holmes into these three episodes, but after seeing Scott's audition<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherlock creator: Andrew Scott\u2019s Moriarty audition was so good we re-wrote the episode for him|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-12/sherlock-creator-andrew-scotts-moriarty-audition-was-so-good-we-re-wrote-the-episode-for-him/|website=[[Radio Times]]|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=31 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100402/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-12/sherlock-creator-andrew-scotts-moriarty-audition-was-so-good-we-re-wrote-the-episode-for-him/|archive-date=1 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> they realised that they \"just had to do a confrontation scene. We had to do a version of the scene in '[[The Final Problem]]' in which the two archenemies meet each other.\"<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" />\n\nThe remainder of the regular cast includes Una Stubbs (who has known Cumberbatch since he was four years old, as she had worked with his mother [[Wanda Ventham]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/squidink/2012/05/q_a_with_una_stubbs.php?page=2|title=Q & A With Una Stubbs: The Joy of Victoria Sponges + Getting Sherlock Holmes to Eat|date=9 October 2014|work=LA Weekly|access-date=2 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192202/http://blogs.laweekly.com/squidink/2012/05/q_a_with_una_stubbs.php?page=2|archive-date=2 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Mrs. Hudson and co-creator Mark Gatiss as Mycroft Holmes.<ref name=\"bbcpressep2\">{{cite web |title=Network TV BBC Week 31: Sunday 1&nbsp;August 2010 |work=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk31/sun.shtml#sun_sherlock |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720160047/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk31/sun.shtml#sun_sherlock |archive-date=20 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Vinette Robinson]], [[Jonathan Aris]] and [[Louise Brealey]] play the recurring roles of Sergeant Sally Donovan, Philip Anderson and Molly Hooper, respectively.\n\n[[Amanda Abbington]], Freeman's then-real life partner, plays [[Mary Morstan]], Watson's girlfriend and eventual wife. In Series 3, [[Wanda Ventham]] and [[Timothy Carlton]], Cumberbatch's actual parents, are introduced as Sherlock and Mycroft's parents.\n\nGuest appearances included [[Phil Davis (actor)|Phil Davis]] as Jefferson Hope,<ref name=\"s1ep1\">{{cite episode |title=A Study in Pink |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Steven Moffat, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=25 July 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=1}}</ref> [[Paul Chequer]] as DI Dimmock,<ref name=\"s1ep2\">{{cite episode |title=The Blind Banker |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Stephen Thompson, dir. Euros Lyn |network=BBC |airdate=1 August 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=2}}</ref> [[Zoe Telford]] as Sarah,<ref name=\"s1ep2\" /> [[Gemma Chan]] as Soo Lin Yao,<ref name=\"s1ep2\" /> [[John Sessions]] as Kenny Prince,<ref name=\"s1ep3\">{{cite episode |title=The Great Game |series=Sherlock |credits=wr. Mark Gatiss, dir. Paul McGuigan |network=BBC |airdate=8 August 2010 |seriesno=1 |number=3}}</ref> [[Haydn Gwynne]] as Miss Wenceslas,<ref name=\"s1ep3\" /> [[Deborah Moore]]<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\">Mark Gatiss, Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman. DVD audio commentary for \"The Great Game\"</ref> as one of Moriarty's victims and [[Peter Davison]] as the voice-over in the planetarium.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" /> Series two's \"[[A Scandal in Belgravia]]\" featured [[Lara Pulver]] as [[Irene Adler]],<ref name=\"telegraph=iplayer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9297689/Sherlock-episode-with-naked-Lara-Pulver-most-watched-show-on-BBC-iPlayer.html|title=Sherlock episode with naked Lara Pulver most watched show on BBC iPlayer|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=29 May 2012|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601223433/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9297689/Sherlock-episode-with-naked-Lara-Pulver-most-watched-show-on-BBC-iPlayer.html|archive-date=1 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> while \"[[The Hounds of Baskerville]]\" featured [[Russell Tovey]] as Henry Knight.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a327636/russell-tovey-to-appear-in-sherlock.html|title=Russell Tovey to appear in 'Sherlock'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=30 June 2011|accessdate=24 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716073510/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a327636/russell-tovey-to-appear-in-sherlock.html|archive-date=16 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final episode of series 2, the role of Rufus Bruhl was played by Edward Holtom, while [[Katherine Parkinson]] played journalist Kitty Riley. The first episode of series 3 featured [[Derren Brown]].\n\n=== Production design and filming ===\nThe show was produced by Hartswood Films for BBC Wales, while [[BBC Worldwide]] also provided co-production funding.<ref name=\"Parker\" /><ref>{{cite news|last= Clarke|first= Steve|date= 1 October 2009|url= https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009441.html?categoryId=3750&cs=1|title= Can Holmes solve co-prod mystery?|work= Variety|publisher= Reed Business Information|accessdate= 2 October 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091006143222/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009441.html?categoryid=3750&cs=1|archive-date= 6 October 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Production was also co-produced by [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]], a network of public-service broadcasters in the United States, for [[WGBH-TV]]'s ''[[Mystery!|Masterpiece Mystery!]]'' strand.<ref name=\"weisman\">{{cite news|last= Weisman |first=Jon|date= 22 February 2010|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118015609.html?categoryId=14&cs=1|title= PBS climbs 'Upstairs' with BBC|work= Variety|publisher= Reed Business Information|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"press12july\">{{cite web |author=BBC Press Office |date=12 July 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/07_july/12/sherlock.shtml |title=''Sherlock'' Press pack |accessdate=12 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715091537/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/07_july/12/sherlock.shtml |archive-date=15 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming of the pilot episode, written by Moffat and directed by [[Coky Giedroyc]], commenced in January 2009.<ref>{{cite press release |title=BBC Drama announces 'Sherlock', a new crime drama for BBC One |publisher=BBC Press Office |date=19 December 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/12_december/19/sherlock.shtml |accessdate=27 December 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I1ym6vEq?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/12_december/19/sherlock.shtml |archive-date=11 July 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following January (2010), the first set of three episodes entered production. Paul McGuigan directed the first and third episodes and [[Euros Lyn]] directed the second.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=Hartswood Films|date= January 2010|url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/pdf/sherlock-start-of-shoot-press-release.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716174250/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/pdf/sherlock-start-of-shoot-press-release.pdf|archivedate= 16 July 2011|format=PDF|title= Filming Begins on 'Sherlock'|accessdate=28 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Levine|first=Nick|date=17 April 2010|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/tubetalk/a214862/mark-gatiss-talks-who-sherlock.html|title=Mark Gatiss talks 'Who', 'Sherlock'|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=28 May 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8J9IGHv?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/tubetalk/a214862/mark-gatiss-talks-who-sherlock.html|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The three episodes were filmed in reverse order of their broadcast.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" />\n[[File:Shooting Sherlock.JPG|thumb|left|[[North Gower Street]] in London was used for exterior shots of the location of Holmes' \"Baker Street\" residence<ref name=\"londontown\" />|alt=A street, with crew members looking towards a caf\u00e9 and a house]]\nGatiss says that they wanted to \"fetishise modern London in the way that the period versions fetishise Victorian London\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Production was based at Hartswood Films' Cardiff production unit, Hartswood Films West, which was opened in late 2009 to take advantage of the BBC's planned [[Cardiff Bay]] \"drama village\". Production of the first two series was based at [[Upper Boat Studios]], where ''Doctor Who'' had been produced.<ref>{{cite news|last= Parker|first= Robin|date= 20 August 2009|url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/indies/hartswood-set-to-develop-projects-from-welsh-office/5004700.article|title= Hartswood set to develop projects from Welsh office|format= subscription access|work= Broadcast|publisher= Emap Media|accessdate= 20 August 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120405095945/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/indies/hartswood-set-to-develop-projects-from-welsh-office/5004700.article|archive-date= 5 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Upstairs\">{{cite web |first= Maggie |last=Brown |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/30501/upstairs-downstairs-the-return-of-a-classic | title= Upstairs, Downstairs: The Return of a Classic |work=[[The Stage]] | date= 3 December 2010 | accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> Cardiff was more economical than in London, with some good matches for parts of London.<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Some architecture could not be faked, so location shooting in the English capital was necessary.<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> The location shots for 221B Baker Street were filmed at 187 [[North Gower Street]]<ref name=\"londontown\">{{Cite journal|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonBlog/Nelsons/8800/Holmes_sweet_Holmes |title=Holmes sweet Holmes |date=26 July 2010 |publisher=London Town |first=Sadie |last=Nelson |journal=Nelson's Column |accessdate=4 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803171413/http://londontown.com/LondonBlog/Nelsons/8800/Holmes_sweet_Holmes |archivedate=3 August 2010 |df= }}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 Baker Street was impractical because of heavy traffic, and the number of things labelled \"Sherlock Holmes\", which would need to be disguised.<ref name=\"s1ep3-comm\" /> Executive producer [[Beryl Vertue]] explains how it was important to design the entirety of Sherlock's flat as a contemporary set, yet still convey his eccentricity. He would not, she says, live somewhere \"too suburban\" or \"too modern\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\nSpeedy's, the sandwich shop below the flat used as Holmes' residence, reported a sharp rise in new customers who recognised it from the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rackl|first=Lori|title=Hunting for \u2018Sherlock\u2019 at Speedy\u2019s, a London cafe|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2015/12/19/speedy-quick-rise-fame-elementary/mUib4MZQt6xvOc32qbMPFL/story.html|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Lynnette|title=Speedy's Cafe: Starring in 'Sherlock' is Part of the Family Business |url=https://www.popmatters.com/170857-speedys-cafe-starring-in-sherlock-is-part-of-the-family-business-2495761536.html|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|date=1 May 2013|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nCostumes for the pilot were designed by [[BAFTA Cymru]] award-winning costume designer Ray Holman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.costume-designer.co.uk/cv/sherlock/|title=Sherlock|publisher=Ray Holman website|accessdate=21 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805144529/http://www.costume-designer.co.uk/portfolio-items/sherlock-pilot/|archive-date=5 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Cumberbatch wore a \u00a31,000 [[Belstaff]] coat in the series.<ref name=\"indep-costume\" /> Sarah Arthur, the series' costume designer, explained how she achieved the detective's look. \"Holmes wouldn't have any interest in fashion so I went for classic suits with a modern twist: narrow-leg trousers and a two-button, slim-cut jacket. I also went for slim-cut shirts and a sweeping coat for all the action scenes\u2014it looks great against the London skyline.\"<ref name=\"indep-costume\">{{cite news |first1=Paul |last1=Bignell |first2=Rachel |last2=Shields |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/sherlock-chic-fashion-its-elementary-thanks-to-bbc-2046500.html |title=Sherlock chic! Fashion? It's elementary, thanks to BBC |work=The Independent |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=10 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022020124/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/sherlock-chic-fashion-its-elementary-thanks-to-bbc-2046500.html |archive-date=22 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe writers say that they did not want to force modernity onto the story.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> There were some creative challenges, such as the decision to include the sign \"221B\" on Holmes' front door. Gatiss and Moffat reflect that in the modern world the door would only display the number of the house, and there would be doorbells for each flat. The full house number is so iconic that they felt unable to change it.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> The writers also decided that the lead characters would address each other by their first names, rather than the traditional Holmes and Watson.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" /> This was also reflected in the title of the series. Director Paul McGuigan came up with the idea of putting text messages on the screen instead of having cut-away shots of a hand holding the phone.<ref name=\"s1ep1-comm\" />\n\n[[File:Martin Freeman + Benedict Cumberbatch.JPG|thumb|[[Martin Freeman]] and [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] filming the third series of ''Sherlock'', August 2013]]\nThe producers found it difficult to coordinate the schedules of the principal players and Moffat and Gatiss for a second series. Cumberbatch and Freeman both worked on the 2012 film ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]'', and Moffat continued as ''Doctor Who''{{'}}s showrunner and head writer. In response to the time pressure, ''The Guardian'' asserted, the series \"features reworkings of three of Conan Doyle's most recognised tales\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> Gatiss says that there had been an argument for producing these tales over three years, but Moffat explained that they rejected \"deferred pleasure\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> The relationship between Holmes and Watson developed during the second series, with Watson being less amazed by Sherlock's deductive abilities; Watson acted as the primary detective in the second episode, \"The Hounds of Baskerville\".<ref name=\"guard171211\" /> The cast and production team were more confident during the second series' production following the positive audience and critical reaction to the first series.<ref name=\"ds-moff-trf\" /><ref name=\"uncovered\">\"Sherlock Uncovered\", documentary on ''Sherlock'' series 2 DVD/Blu-ray release</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nThe theme and [[incidental music]] were composed by [[David Arnold]] and [[Michael Price (composer)|Michael Price]].<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Arnold explains that he and Price worked with the producers to \"come up with a central theme and character\" for the series, then found what was \"going to be the defining sound of this show\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Pieces were often constructed using [[synthesizer]]s, but the tracks used for the show were recorded using real musicians, Arnold says, to bring the music \"to life\".<ref name=\"unlocking\" /> Similarly, Price comments that the musicians can adapt their performance of a [[film score|score]] by responding to footage from the show.<ref name=\"unlocking\" />\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{main|List of Sherlock episodes}}\nFour series, each consisting of three episodes, have been produced. The first series was initially broadcast in July and August 2010 on the BBC, later premiering on [[PBS|Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) in the United States in October 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest Sherlock Hears a 'Who'|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2010/10/22/arts/television/22sherlock.html |first=Mike |last=Hale |work=The New York Times |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref> A second series of three episodes was first broadcast in the UK in January 2012, and then in the U.S. during May 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Holmes and Watson, Back to Bantering |url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/05/05/arts/television/sherlock-returns-on-masterpiece-mystery.html |first=Neil |last=Genzlinger |work=The New York Times |date=4 May 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627235122/http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/05/05/arts/television/sherlock-returns-on-masterpiece-mystery.html |archive-date=27 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series premiered in the UK on 1 January 2014 and in the US on 19 January 2014. The series has been sold to 180 territories.<ref name=\"S5Lang\" /> A special episode premiered on 1 January 2016, on BBC One and PBS, marking the first time the series has aired on the same day in the UK and U.S.<ref name=\"SpecialAirdate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/24/sherlock-date|title=Sherlock finally gets return date, plus new full trailer|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=24 October 2015|accessdate=24 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025134601/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/24/sherlock-date|archive-date=25 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth series began airing on BBC One and PBS on 1 January 2017 and concluded on 15 January 2017.<ref name=\"S4Airdates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-06/full-schedule-of-sherlock-series-4-air-dates-confirmed|title=Full schedule of Sherlock series 4 air dates confirmed|author=Paul Jones|work=RadioTimes|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206235753/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-06/full-schedule-of-sherlock-series-4-air-dates-confirmed|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{:List of Sherlock episodes}}\n\n=== Series 1 (2010) ===\nThe first episode, \"[[A Study in Pink]]\", loosely based upon the first Sherlock Holmes novel ''[[A Study in Scarlet]]'', was written by Moffat and directed by Paul McGuigan. The story depicts the introduction of Sherlock to John, and them entering a [[Roommate|flatshare]] at Baker Street in London, and then their investigation into a series of deaths, initially believed to be suicides. Mycroft Holmes, Sherlock's older brother, played by [[Mark Gatiss]], also appears for the first time. The episode was first broadcast simultaneously on BBC One and BBC HD on 25 July 2010.<ref name=\"guard-ep1-fig\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Sweney |title=Sherlock Holmes more popular than Tom Cruise |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/26/sherlock-holmes-more-viewers-top-gear |work=The Guardian |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=4 August 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8K9JnQM?url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/26/sherlock-holmes-more-viewers-top-gear |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"press\">{{cite web |author=BBC Press Office |date=8 July 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk30/unplaced.shtml#unplaced_sherlock |title=\"Network TV BBC Week 30: Unplaced\" Press release |accessdate=14 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8JvGks0?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk30/unplaced.shtml#unplaced_sherlock |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe second episode, \"[[The Blind Banker]]\", was first broadcast on 1 August 2010. Written by [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]] and directed by Euros Lyn, the episode depicts Holmes being hired by an old university acquaintance to investigate a mysterious break-in at a bank in the [[City of London]].<ref name=\"guard-ep2-fig\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Deans |title=Sherlock on the case with 6.4m |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/02/sherlock-bbc1-tv-ratings |work=The Guardian |date=2 August 2010 |accessdate=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801234841/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/02/sherlock-bbc1-tv-ratings |archive-date=1 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first series concluded with \"[[The Great Game (Sherlock)|The Great Game]]\", first broadcast on 8 August 2010. The episode introduces the character of archenemy James Moriarty (played by Andrew Scott) to the series, who sets Holmes deadlines to solve a series of apparently unrelated cases. Written by Mark Gatiss and directed by McGuigan, \"The Great Game\" ends with a cliffhanger in which Sherlock and Moriarty reach a standoff involving a bomb attached to a vest removed moments earlier from Watson.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Sherlock |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/09/sherlock-benedict-cumberbatch-tv-review |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 April 2011 |date=9 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922145409/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/09/sherlock-benedict-cumberbatch-tv-review |archive-date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 2 (2012) ===\nAfter the high ratings for \"A Study in Pink\", the BBC was reportedly eager to produce more episodes.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC 'keen to film more Sherlock' |first=Christian |last=Tobin |date=27 July 2010 |work=Digital Spy |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a251236/bbc-keen-to-film-more-sherlock.html |accessdate=28 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727231812/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a251236/bbc-keen-to-film-more-sherlock.html |archive-date=27 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 10 August 2010, it was confirmed that ''Sherlock'' had been renewed for a second series.<ref name=\"guard-renew\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/10/sherlock-second-series-bbc |title=Sherlock to return for second series |last=Frost |first=Vicky |date=10 August 2010 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=10 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922010019/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/10/sherlock-second-series-bbc |archive-date=22 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the 2011 convention, Gatiss confirmed which stories would be adapted, and that the writers of the first series would each write an episode for series two.<ref name=\"ign-kapow\">{{cite web |first=Leigh |last=Singer |title=Kapow! 11: Ideal Holmes: Mark Gatiss on the new series of Sherlock and Doctor Who |date=10 April 2011 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/116/1160905p1.html |work=IGN.com |accessdate=26 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110413151336/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/116/1160905p1.html |archive-date=13 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Acknowledging that \"[[A Scandal in Bohemia]]\", \"[[The Hound of the Baskervilles]]\" and \"[[The Final Problem]]\" are amongst the best-known Holmes stories, Gatiss explained, \"We knew after having a successful first run that the natural order would be to do three of the most famous [stories].\"<ref name=\"ign-kapow\" /> \"There's the question of how to go out on a cliffhanger and then the thematic things of the three stories, where we were trying to get to and what Sherlock and John's relationship is a little further on. You can't just go back to: 'You have no emotions.' 'I don't care.' You've got to move on somewhere and make sure the other characters have something of a journey too.\"<ref name=\"ign-kapow\" /> Paul McGuigan directed the first two episodes,<ref>{{cite news |title=Director's cut: How Hollywood director witnessed real gore for new tv drama |date=7 March 2011 |first=Brian |last=McIver |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2011/03/07/director-s-cut-how-hollywood-director-witnessed-real-gore-for-new-tv-drama-86908-22972460/ |work=Daily Record |publisher=Scottish Daily Record and Sunday Mail Ltd. |accessdate=26 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324071116/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2011/03/07/director-s-cut-how-hollywood-director-witnessed-real-gore-for-new-tv-drama-86908-22972460/ |archive-date=24 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''Doctor Who'' director [[Toby Haynes]] handled the last one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96fgOz0uDzs|title=Video: Doctor Who at Wondercon 2011 (View from 36:35)|work=YouTube|accessdate=20 April 2011|quote=So what's next for you?\" \"I'm doing ''Sherlock''.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053827/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96fgOz0uDzs|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The second series of three 90-minute episodes was initially planned to air in late 2011,<ref>\n{{cite web |title=New commissions and return of Sherlock for BBC One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/08_august/28/bbcone.shtml |work=BBC Press Office |date=28 August 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916083512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/08_august/28/bbcone.shtml |archive-date=16 September 2010 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> but was delayed until early January 2012.\n\n\"[[A Scandal in Belgravia]]\", written by Steven Moffat and directed by Paul McGuigan, was first broadcast on 1 January 2012. Loosely based on \"A Scandal in Bohemia\", the episode depicts Holmes's quest to retrieve compromising photos of a minor royal held on the camera phone of Irene Adler ([[Lara Pulver]]), a ruthless and brilliant [[dominatrix#Professional|dominatrix]] who also trades in classified information extracted from her rich and powerful clients.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 January 2012 |title=Last Night's TV: Sherlock, BBC 1 |newspaper=The Independent |first=Tom |last=Sutcliffe |authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster) |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv-sherlock-bbc-1-6283989.html |accessdate=4 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108021204/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv-sherlock-bbc-1-6283989.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Barts.jpg|thumb|The resolution of Sherlock's faked suicide from the roof of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] in London attracted speculation in social media and newspapers.]]\nMark Gatiss wrote \"[[The Hounds of Baskerville]]\", which investigates the strange activities at a military base. Aware that ''The Hound of the Baskervilles'', first published in 1902, was one of the most famous of Conan Doyle's original stories, Gatiss felt a greater responsibility to include familiar elements of the story than he does when adapting the lesser-known stories.<ref name=\"gat-ds\">{{cite web |title='Sherlock' Mark Gatiss Q&A: 'Horror is a big part of Sherlock Holmes' |date=5 January 2012 |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a358335/sherlock-mark-gatiss-qa-horror-is-a-big-part-of-sherlock-holmes.html |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=8 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108065805/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/interviews/a358335/sherlock-mark-gatiss-qa-horror-is-a-big-part-of-sherlock-holmes.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sherlock writer Steven Moffat furious with sexist claim |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2012/01/04/sherlock-writer-steven-moffat-furious-with-sexist-claim-91466-30062866/2/ |first=Simon |last=Gaskell |work=Wales Online |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113091342/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2012/01/04/sherlock-writer-steven-moffat-furious-with-sexist-claim-91466-30062866/2/ |archivedate=13 January 2012 |df= }}</ref> Russell Tovey appeared as Henry Knight, a man whose father was ripped apart by a gigantic hound on [[Dartmoor]] 20 years earlier. Directed by McGuigan, the episode was first broadcast on 8 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Borgen; Sherlock |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/07/tv-review-borgen-sherlock |date=7 January 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=8 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104233313/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/07/tv-review-borgen-sherlock |archive-date=4 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe second series concluded with \"[[The Reichenbach Fall]]\". Steve Thompson wrote the episode, which was directed by Toby Haynes, who had previously directed many of Moffat's ''Doctor Who'' episodes. First broadcast on 15 January 2012, the episode follows Moriarty's plot to discredit and kill Sherlock Holmes, concluding with Holmes appearing to die by suicide.<ref name=\"missed-clues\" /> The episode was inspired by Conan Doyle's story \"The Final Problem\", in which Holmes and Moriarty are presumed to have fallen to their deaths from the [[Reichenbach Falls]] in [[Switzerland]]. Moffat felt that he and co-creator Gatiss had outdone Conan Doyle in their version of Holmes' fall and Moffat added that, in that much-discussed sequence, there was still \"a clue everybody's missed\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title=Sherlock: vital missing clue behind death fall |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/sherlock-vital-missing-clue-death-fall |date=20 January 2012 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=28 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809132914/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/sherlock-vital-missing-clue-death-fall |archive-date=9 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Christmas mini-episode (2013) ===\nBBC One premiered a seven-minute ''Sherlock'' mini-episode over the 2013 Christmas period entitled \"Many Happy Returns\". The episode is available via [[BBC iPlayer]], [[BBC Red Button]] service, and BBC's [[YouTube]] channel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwntNANJCOE|title=Sherlock Mini-Episode: Many Happy Returns&nbsp;\u2014 Sherlock Series 3 Prequel&nbsp;\u2014 BBC One|website=BBC Youtube channel|date=24 December 2013|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026133016/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwntNANJCOE|archive-date=26 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and acts as a prequel to the third series.\n\nThe synopsis for the episode reads \"Sherlock has been gone for two years. But someone isn't quite convinced that he's dead.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws|title=''Sherlock'' profile, BBC One|work=BBC|access-date=29 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105043656/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws|archive-date=5 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The 'someone' turns out to be [[List of Sherlock characters#Philip Anderson|Anderson]], the forensics technician from series 1 and 2 (who has now lost his job due to his obsessive conviction that the detective still lives). He had a long-standing mistrust of Sherlock, yet is now one of the few people who believes Sherlock is alive, and throughout the episode is trying to convince Lestrade. Anderson tracks him via various mysterious events from Tibet to New Delhi to Germany in which he seems to be involved and points out that the incidents are getting progressively closer to London.\n\n=== Series 3 (2014) ===\nAfter the end of the final episode of the second series, Moffat and Gatiss both announced on Twitter that a third series had been commissioned at the same time as series two,<ref name=\"bbc20120116\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock to return for third series |date=16 January 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16573066 |work=BBC News |accessdate=16 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116180916/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16573066 |archive-date=16 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a part of the resolution to \"The Reichenbach Fall\" was filmed concurrently with series two.<ref name=\"missed-clues\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title='There is a clue everybody's missed': Sherlock writer Steven Moffat interviewed |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211731/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Without revealing whether Moriarty also faked his own death at the end of series two, Moffat suggested that Moriarty will not feature heavily in future series of ''Sherlock''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steven Moffat: expect new Sherlock villains |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-01/steven-moffat-expect-new-sherlock-villains |date=1 March 2012 |work=Radio Times |publisher=Immediate Media Company Limited |accessdate=13 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303224238/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-01/steven-moffat-expect-new-sherlock-villains |archive-date=3 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Sherlock' creator: 'Moriarty won't return' |url=https://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/sherlock-creator-moriarty-wont-return/261748 |date=2 March 2012 |work=NME |accessdate=13 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304201201/http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/sherlock-creator-moriarty-wont-return/261748 |archive-date=4 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[The Empty Hearse]]\", written by Mark Gatiss and directed by Jeremy Lovering, is the first episode of Series 3 and was first broadcast on 1 January 2014. Inspired by \"[[The Adventure of the Empty House]]\" by [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]], the episode follows Sherlock Holmes' return to London and reunion with John Watson, and their subsequent solving of an underground terrorist network. The episode achieved an official rating of 12.72&nbsp;million viewers,<ref>{{Cite web|title = BARB|url = http://www.barb.co.uk/|website = www.barb.co.uk|access-date = 5 February 2016|archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/5gJ2i7uOI?url=http://www.barb.co.uk/|archive-date = 25 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> making it the [[Highest rated drama episodes in the United Kingdom in 2014|highest rated drama episode shown on UK television in 2014]].\n\nIn \"[[The Sign of Three]]\", written by Stephen Thompson, Mark Gatiss and [[Steven Moffat]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03ny7ng | title=The Sign of Three, Series 3 Episode 2 | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=bbc.co.uk | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102140549/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03ny7ng | archive-date=2 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> Watson and Mary Morstan<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-01/sherlock-series-3-episode-2-the-sign-of-three-programme-guide | title=Sherlock series 3 episode 2 The Sign of Three programme guide | publisher=[[Radio Times]] | work=radiotimes.com | date=1 January 2014 | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103070719/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-01/sherlock-series-3-episode-2-the-sign-of-three-programme-guide | archive-date=3 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> get married. The episode takes place during the wedding reception and the story is told through flashbacks. The episode title is inspired by ''[[The Sign of the Four]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/04/10/love-interest-for-john-watson-in-new-sherlock-episode-the-sign-of-three-3591590/ | title=Love interest for John Watson in new Sherlock episode The Sign of Three? | publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | work=metro.co.uk | date=10 April 2013 | accessdate=2 January 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207030556/http://metro.co.uk/2013/04/10/love-interest-for-john-watson-in-new-sherlock-episode-the-sign-of-three-3591590/ | archive-date=7 December 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> and was first broadcast on 5 January 2014.\n\nThe final episode \"[[His Last Vow]]\" was first broadcast on 12 January 2014, on [[BBC One]], and written by Steven Moffat, directed by [[Nick Hurran]] and is based on Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's \"[[The Adventure of Charles Augustus Milverton]]\". This case leads Sherlock into conflict with [[List of Sherlock characters#Charles Augustus Magnussen|Charles Augustus Magnussen]] ([[Lars Mikkelsen]]), a \"terrifying\" villain who was introduced as an unnamed villain in episode one. [[Mary Morstan]] and Sherlock Holmes both break into Magnussen's office, where, having surprised each other, Mary shoots Sherlock.  Later, Holmes deduces that Mary was formerly a [[Spy|secret agent]], and reveals this to Watson.  Holmes and Watson try to get Magnussen arrested, but their attempt fails, and Holmes shoots Magnussen to stop him from blackmailing Mary Watson. Mycroft arranges that Sherlock will be exiled from the United Kingdom instead of being tried for murder. As Sherlock's plane takes off, every video screen in London broadcasts the image of Moriarty, and Sherlock is recalled to deal with the crisis associated with Moriarty's potential return.\n\nThe third series aired in the United States on PBS over a period of three weeks, airing late January to early February 2014.\n\n=== Special (2016) ===\n[[File:Una Stubbs, filming Sherlock (2015).jpg|thumb|right|Stubbs pictured in costume for the episode, February 2015]]\n{{main|The Abominable Bride}}\nOn 2 July 2014, it was announced there would be a special episode broadcast between the third and fourth series. Filming began on 5 January 2015 and wrapped on 10 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/sherlock-miss-me|title=\"Miss me?\" The nation's favourite detective returns to BBC One|website=BBC Media Centre|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124170224/http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/sherlock-miss-me|archive-date=24 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/sherlock-special-begins-filming|title=Sherlock Special Begins Filming|website=Radio Times|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=13 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212084805/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/sherlock-special-begins-filming|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/drmuig/status/565245574564569088|title=Sherlock Special Filming Wrapped|website=Twitter|date=10 February 2015|accessdate=10 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305114238/https://twitter.com/drmuig/status/565245574564569088|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"S4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/sherlock-announcement-special-confirmed-three-3799440 |title=Sherlock announcement: Special confirmed with 'three new episodes' as #221back riddle is revealed |last=Hyland |first=Karen |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]] |date=2 July 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702224308/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/sherlock-announcement-special-confirmed-three-3799440 |archive-date=2 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat confirmed the episode is set in Victorian London, saying, \"The special is its own thing. We wouldn't have done the story we're doing, and the way we're doing it, if we didn't have this special. It's not part of the run of three episodes. So we had this to do it \u2026 It's kind of in its own little bubble.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/16/sherlock-special-victorian-|title=''Sherlock'' co-creator confirms special is set in Victorian London|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=16 March 2015|accessdate=18 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317234014/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/16/sherlock-special-victorian-|archive-date=17 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the title of the episode was announced. It was broadcast on 1 January 2016 at 9:00&nbsp;pm local time on BBC One in the UK, and on [[PBS]] in the US.<ref name=\"SpecialAirdate\" /> The episode was [[simulcast]] in British cinemas on 1 January, and was shown on 5 and 6 January 2016 in selected cinemas throughout the US.<ref>{{cite web| title=Sherlock: The Abominable Bride| url=http://www.fandango.com/sherlock:theabominablebride_188357/movieoverview| website=Fandango| publisher=NBCUniversal| accessdate=1 January 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101204957/http://www.fandango.com/sherlock:theabominablebride_188357/movieoverview| archive-date=1 January 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> Exclusive bonus material in the cinema presentation included a guided tour of 221B Baker Street from Steven Moffat and a look behind the scenes at how the special episode was made featuring all the lead cast and crew.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vue Cinemas |url=http://www.myvue.com/latest-movies/info/cinema/exeter/film/sherlock-the-abominable-bride |archive-url=https://archive.is/20160114094550/http://www.myvue.com/latest-movies/info/cinema/exeter/film/sherlock-the-abominable-bride |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 January 2016 |website=vue cinemas |accessdate=5 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 4 (2017) ===\nBy October 2013, a fourth series was commissioned, with scripts planned.<ref name=\"fourthseries\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/09/sherlock-back-fourth-series-steven-moffat |title=Sherlock will be back for fourth series, says producer Steven Moffat |last1=Brown |first1=Maggie |last2= |first2= |date=9 January 2014 |website=The Guardian Australia |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=11 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114215023/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/09/sherlock-back-fourth-series-steven-moffat |archive-date=14 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/sherlock-creators-reveal-already-series-6470060 | title= Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman commissioned Sherlock series 4 themselves says Steven Moffat | magazine= Radio Times | date= 14 October 2013 | accessdate= 7 January 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140107050844/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/sherlock-creators-reveal-already-series-6470060 | archive-date= 7 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> Moffat told [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Telegraph'']] in January 2014, \"we're all keen to continue\", but said it had been difficult to co-ordinate the lead actors' schedules.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sherlock creator denies plot holes in BBC drama |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10553570/Sherlock-creator-denies-plot-holes-in-BBC-drama.html |first1=Hayley |last1=Dixon |first2=Joe |last2=Kavanagh |date=6 January 2014 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=7 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107051843/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10553570/Sherlock-creator-denies-plot-holes-in-BBC-drama.html |archive-date=7 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming began on 4 April 2016 at [[Pinewood Studio Wales]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/sherlock-season-4-begins-filming-today|title='Sherlock' Series 4 begins filming!|work=CultBox|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=5 April 2016|last=Martin|first=William|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407014030/http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/sherlock-season-4-begins-filming-today|archive-date=7 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and lasted until 5 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/24/comic-con-2016-sherlock-panel|title=Comic-Con 2016: Sherlock panel reveals three key names to tease series 4|last=Smith|first=C. Molly|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=24 July 2016|accessdate=24 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725150922/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/24/comic-con-2016-sherlock-panel|archive-date=25 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BIvNCLGg1vx/ |title=It's a WRAP on #sherlock series IV 2016 |last=Caron|first=Benjamin|publisher=Instagram|date=5 August 2016|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> In May 2016 it was announced that [[Toby Jones]] had been cast as a villain from [[Sherlock Holmes]] lore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/Check-Out-Major-Villain-Sherlock-Season-4-138327.html|title=Check Out The Major Villain in Sherlock Series 4|last=Hurley|first=Laura|work=Cinemablend|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518232240/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/Check-Out-Major-Villain-Sherlock-Season-4-138327.html|archive-date=18 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth series premiered on 1 January 2017, with \"[[The Six Thatchers]]\".<ref name=\"S4Airdates\" /> The second episode \"[[The Lying Detective]]\" aired on 8 January 2017; the last episode \"[[The Final Problem (Sherlock)|The Final Problem]]\" aired on 15 January 2017.\n\n=== Future ===\nIn January 2014, Moffat stated that a fifth series had been plotted by himself and Gatiss;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/sherlock-writers-plot-fourth-and-fifth-series-9048981.html|title=Sherlock writers plot fourth and fifth series|last=Denham|first=Jess|work=The Independent|date=9 January 2014|accessdate=14 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809075954/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/sherlock-writers-plot-fourth-and-fifth-series-9048981.html|archive-date=9 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> however, by the release of the fourth series in January 2017, they had not yet decided whether to produce it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-15/mark-gatiss-and-steven-moffat-reveal-where-sherlock-could-go-in-series-5|title=Mark Gatiss and Steven Moffat reveal where Sherlock could go in series 5|last=Dowell|first=Ben|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116174355/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-15/mark-gatiss-and-steven-moffat-reveal-where-sherlock-could-go-in-series-5|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Cumberbatch and Moffat in particular have expressed interest in continuing at some point in the future, but there are no immediate plans.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jeffery|first1=Morgan|title=Sherlock series 5 air date, cast, episodes, news and everything you need to know|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/sherlock/feature/a819122/sherlock-season-5-air-date-cast-episodes-news-and-everything-you-need-to-know/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212013430/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/sherlock/feature/a819122/sherlock-season-5-air-date-cast-episodes-news-and-everything-you-need-to-know/|archive-date=12 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As to the future of the series, Gatiss stated that due to the conflicting schedules of Cumberbatch and Freeman, a potential fifth series is still up in the air.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|title=Steven Moffat speaks out on Sherlock's future: \"It rather depends on our two stars\"|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/cult/a819195/sherlock-series-5-steven-moffat-speaks-out-benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman/|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=17 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119120840/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/cult/a819195/sherlock-series-5-steven-moffat-speaks-out-benedict-cumberbatch-martin-freeman/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; text-align:center; margin:10px\"\n|+ [[Metacritic]] ratings per series\n|-\n|{{Graph:Chart|width=200|height=100|yAxisMin=70|yAxisMax=100|x=Series 1, Series 2, Series3|y=85,91,88}}\n|-\n|<!-- begin inner table -->\n{| style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 1 (2010)|Series 1]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 2 (2012)|Series 2]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 3 (2014)|Series 3]]}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Rating\n| {{formatnum:85}}<ref name=MetacriticS1>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=30 November 2015 |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127200048/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=27 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:91}}<ref name=MetacriticS2>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 2 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=30 November 2015 |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120075203/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-2 |archive-date=20 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:88}}<ref name=MetacriticS3>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-3 |title=Sherlock: Series 3 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=2 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101024328/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock/season-3 |archive-date=1 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- end inner table -->\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; text-align:center; margin:10px\"\n|+ [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ratings per series\n|-\n|{{Graph:Chart|width=200|height=100|yAxisMin=50|yAxisMax=100|x=Series 1, Series 2, Series 3, Series 4|y=93,94,91,56}}\n|-\n|<!-- begin inner table -->\n{| style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 1 (2010)|Series 1]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 2 (2012)|Series 2]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 3 (2014)|Series 3]]}}\n! scope=col | {{Small|[[List of Sherlock episodes#Series 4 (2017)|Series 4]]}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Rating\n| {{formatnum:93}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s01</ref>\n| {{formatnum:94}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s02</ref>\n| {{formatnum:91}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s03</ref>\n| {{formatnum:56}}<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/s04</ref>\n|}\n<!-- end inner table -->\n|}\n\nThe show has received critical acclaim, sustaining positive reviews across its first three series. However, its fourth series received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherlock series 4: The most furiously outraged critics|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/sherlock-outraged-critical-reviews/|website=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129054352/https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/sherlock-outraged-critical-reviews/|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Shoemaker|first=Allison|title=The frustrating, brilliant Sherlock stays frustrating right to the end|url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-frustrating-brilliant-sherlock-stays-frustrating-r-1798190036|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129100046/https://tv.avclub.com/the-frustrating-brilliant-sherlock-stays-frustrating-r-1798190036|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Series one holds a [[Metacritic]] score of 85/100, based on 17 reviews, and series two scored 91/100, based on 24 reviews, while series three holds a score of 88/100, based on 22 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |title=Sherlock |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=21 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819095203/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=19 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first series holds a 93% rating at critical aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the second holds a 94% rating, and the third series has a 91% approval rating. The fourth series holds a rating of 56%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock/ |title=Sherlock |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504191053/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sherlock |archive-date=4 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first episode rated highly on the [[Appreciation Index]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a252133/sherlock-well-received-by-critics.html |title='Sherlock' well-received by critics |first=Paul |last=Millar |date=28 July 2010 |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=29 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69mEkNAkO?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s129/sherlock/news/a252133/sherlock-well-received-by-critics.html |archive-date=9 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Observer'' said the show was \"a cross between ''[[Withnail and I]]'' and ''[[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|The Bourne Ultimatum]]'', there is also a hint of ''Doctor Who'' about the drama; hardly surprising, since it has been written and created by ''Doctor Who'' writers Mark Gatiss and Steven Moffat.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock Holmes is back... sending texts and using nicotine patches |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/18/sherlock-holmes-is-back-bbc |work=The Observer |date=18 July 2010 |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |accessdate=18 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030175252/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/18/sherlock-holmes-is-back-bbc |archive-date=30 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Dan Martin said, \"It's early days, but the first of three 90-minute movies, 'A Study in Pink', is brilliantly promising. It has the finesse of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' but is indisputably Sherlock Holmes. The deduction sequences are ingenious, and the plot is classic Moffat intricacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Sherlock makes Sunday night TV sexy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jul/23/sherlock-steven-moffat-mark-gatiss |work=The Guardian |date=23 July 2010 |accessdate=25 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8KTy31E?url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jul/23/sherlock-steven-moffat-mark-gatiss |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)|Tom Sutcliffe]] for ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote, \"''Sherlock'' is a triumph, witty and knowing, without ever undercutting the flair and dazzle of the original. It understands that Holmes isn't really about plot but about charisma ... Flagrantly unfaithful to the original in some respects, ''Sherlock'' is wonderfully loyal to it in every way that matters.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Sutcliffe |authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster) |title=The Weekend's TV: Sherlock, Sun, BBC1 Amish: World's Squarest Teenagers, Sun, Channel 4 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-tv-sherlock-sun-bbc1bramish-worlds-squarest-teenagers-sun-channel-4-2035302.html |work=The Independent |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=28 July 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6u8JbHRDe?url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-tv-sherlock-sun-bbc1bramish-worlds-squarest-teenagers-sun-channel-4-2035302.html |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lead actors were commended. Critic Victoria Thorpe said, \"Freeman's dependable, capable Watson unlocks this modern Holmes, a man who now describes himself as 'a high-functioning [[wikt:sociopathy|sociopath]]'.\"<ref name=\"thorpe\" /> Following the second series' opening episode, Sarah Crompton, for ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', asserts that \"Cumberbatch is utterly credible as a man who lives entirely in his cerebellum with little regard for the world outside, mak[ing] ''Sherlock'' the perfect depiction of Holmes for our times\".<ref name=\"crompton\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8987577/The-timeless-appeal-of-Holmess-sexy-logic.html|title=The timeless appeal of Holmes's sexy logic|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 January 2012|first=Sarah|last=Crompton|accessdate=5 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103041614/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8987577/The-timeless-appeal-of-Holmess-sexy-logic.html|archive-date=3 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> David Weigand of the ''[[SF Gate]]'' wrote, \"...a Sherlock for the 21st century.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/TV-review-Fresh-dose-of-fun-in-Sherlock-3248989.php|title=TV review: Fresh dose of fun in 'Sherlock'|last=Wiegand|first=David|date=2010-10-22|website=SFGate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> Jace Lacob of ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' wrote, \"Back from the dead and better than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jacelacob/sherlock-the-empty-hearse-season-3-review|title=\"Sherlock\" Is Back From The Dead And Better Than Ever|last=Lacob|first=Jace|date=2013-12-30|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\nConan Doyle fans were generally appreciative. Gwilym Mumford, for ''The Guardian'', suggested that \"this has to do with the fact that Moffat and Gatiss are enormously knowledgeable about Conan Doyle's work, and their reimagining incorporates big- and small-screen adaptations of Holmes, as well as the original stories. As Gatiss puts it: 'Everything is canonical.' \"<ref name=\"guard171211\">{{cite news |first=Gwilym |last=Mumford |title=Sherlock returns to the BBC: 'He's definitely devilish' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/dec/17/sherlock-bbc-cumberbatch-freeman-interview?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=19 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005124057/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/dec/17/sherlock-bbc-cumberbatch-freeman-interview?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sarah Crompton, for ''The Telegraph'', identifies some of the jokes and allusions intended for fans.<ref name=\"crompton\" /> Commenting specifically on the second series' finale \"The Reichenbach Fall\", ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Sam Wollaston praised the show's faithfulness to Conan Doyle, but also how \"it will wander, taking in mobile phone technology and computer hacking ... But it doesn't feel like cheating; more like an open relationship, agreed by both parties.\"<ref name=\"woll\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wollaston |title=TV review: Sherlock/Call the Midwife/Hugh's Hungry Boys |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/15/tv-review-sherlock?newsfeed=true |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 January 2012 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011021611/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/15/tv-review-sherlock?newsfeed=true |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Sherlock'' was ranked 60th on ''The Guardian'''s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ratings ===\nAccording to overnight data provided by the [[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] (BARB), the highest overnight figure from the first series of ''Sherlock'' was 7.5&nbsp;million for the opening episode, \"A Study in Pink\", whereas the second series averaged over 8 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Marszal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9017545/Sherlock-finale-another-ratings-triumph.html |title=Sherlock finale another ratings triumph |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=16 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117104741/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9017545/Sherlock-finale-another-ratings-triumph.html |archive-date=17 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The three episodes of series two were the three most watched programmes on iPlayer, the BBC's video-on-demand service, between January and April 2012.<ref name=\"telegraph=iplayer\" /> Its opening episode, \"A Scandal in Belgravia\", attracted controversy from the tabloid newspaper ''[[Daily Mail]]'', which reported that Irene Adler's nude scene early in the episode had been met with disapproval from some viewers who were concerned that it had been shown before the 9:00&nbsp;pm [[Watershed (television)|watershed]] hour, before which adult-orientated content is not supposed to air.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC1's Sherlock: no mystery about the Mail's reaction |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2012/jan/03/bbc1-sherlock-mystery-mail |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=3 January 2012 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118072857/https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2012/jan/03/bbc1-sherlock-mystery-mail |archive-date=18 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"repeat\">{{cite news |title=Sherlock: BBC will not remove nude scenes for 7&nbsp;pm repeat |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/04/sherlock-bbc-nude-scenes?newsfeed=true |first=Tara |last=Conlan |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105160131/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/04/sherlock-bbc-nude-scenes?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some critics also took exception to Moffat's treatment of Irene Adler, arguing that she was sexualised,<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite news |title=Is Sherlock sexist? Steven Moffat's wanton women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/jan/03/sherlock-sexist-steven-moffat?newsfeed=true |first=Jane Clare |last=Jones |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105160115/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/jan/03/sherlock-sexist-steven-moffat?newsfeed=true |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> an argument rejected by others, including Moffat.<ref>{{cite web|first=Laura|last=Pledger|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-08/ten-strong-tv-women|title=Ten strong TV women|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=5 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420172628/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-08/ten-strong-tv-women|archive-date=20 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"missed-clue\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title='There is a clue everybody's missed': Sherlock writer Steven Moffat interviewed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211731/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/20/steven-moffat-sherlock-doctor-who?newsfeed=true |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series' conclusion, \"The Reichenbach Fall\", in which Sherlock fakes his suicide by jumping from St Bartholomew's Hospital, led to speculation on forums, social networking sites and in newspaper articles about its resolution.<ref name=\"missed-clue\" />\n\nThe third series became the UK's most watched drama series since 2001. An average 11.82&nbsp;million people watched the series, with about 12.72&nbsp;million tuning in for the first episode.<ref name=\"radiotimes.com\"/> The 2016 New Year's Day special drew 11.64&nbsp;million viewers. The fourth series opened with 11.3&nbsp;million viewers for the first episode, but dropped to 5.9&nbsp;million viewers by the final episode of the fourth series, the lowest overnight ever recorded by the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-16/sherlock-records-its-lowest-ever-overnight-audience-with-59m-tuning-into-series-four-finale/|title=Sherlock records its lowest ever overnight audience with 5.9m tuning into series four finale|last=Cowell|first=Ben|date=16 January 2017|work=Radio Times|accessdate=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117143919/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-16/sherlock-records-its-lowest-ever-overnight-audience-with-59m-tuning-into-series-four-finale|archive-date=17 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Sherlock}}\n\nIn the 2011 [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] awards, the show as a whole won the award for [[British Academy Television Award for Best Drama Series|Best Drama Series]], while Freeman (as Dr Watson) won the award for the [[British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. Cumberbatch was nominated for [[British Academy Television Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]. Andrew Scott won 2012's Best Supporting Actor, beating Freeman, for his work in the second series, which was nominated in other categories.<ref name=\"guard-bafta-2012\">{{cite news |first1=Vicky |last1=Frost |first2=John |last2=Plunkett |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/may/27/bafta-tv-awards-itv-fred-west-drama?newsfeed=true |title=Bafta TV acting awards won by stars of ITV Fred West drama |work=The Guardian |date=27 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306135120/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/may/27/bafta-tv-awards-itv-fred-west-drama?newsfeed=true |archive-date=6 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing multiple nominations for the [[63rd Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2011) and [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2012), the show won multiple Emmys at the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2014), including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Cumberbatch, [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]] for Freeman and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Limited Series, Movie, or Dramatic Special|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special]] for Moffat. It subsequently won the Emmy for Best Television Film at the [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards]] (2016).\n\nThe first series also won the [[Arqiva]] award for the \"best terrestrial show\" at the 2011 Edinburgh International Television Festival.<ref>{{cite news |title=ITV1 named terrestrial channel of the year |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14700111 |work=BBC News |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=28 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828172013/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14700111 |archive-date=28 August 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"A Study in Pink\" and \"A Scandal in Belgravia\" were nominated for [[Emmy Award]]s in a variety of categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: A Study In Pink (Masterpiece) |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-study-pink-masterpiece |work=Emmys.com |accessdate=11 November 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I1yveRgh?url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-study-pink-masterpiece |archive-date=11 July 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"emmy2012\">{{cite web |title=Sherlock: A Scandal in Belgravia (Masterpiece) |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-scandal-belgravia-masterpiece |work=Emmys.com |accessdate=19 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721193933/http://www.emmys.com/shows/sherlock-scandal-belgravia-masterpiece |archive-date=21 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series won several BAFTA Cymru awards: television drama, Director: Fiction (Euros Lyn), Director of Photography: Fiction (Steve Lawes), Production Design (Arwel Wyn Jones), and Make Up & Hair (Claire Pritchard-Jones).<ref name=\"harts=awards\">{{cite web|title=Sherlock Awards 2010/11 |url=http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/programmes/sherlock-awards-201011/ |work=Hartswood Films |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121218092737/http://www.hartswoodfilms.co.uk/programmes/sherlock-awards-201011/ |archivedate=18 December 2012 |df= }}</ref> Charlie Phillips won the 'Editing: Fiction' category at the [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref name=\"harts=awards\" /> The show was also nominated for the YouTube Audience Award.<ref>{{cite news |first1=John |last1=Plunkett |first2=Josh |last2=Halliday |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/22/sherlock-wins-best-drama-award-baftas |title=BBC's Sherlock wins best drama award at Baftas |date=22 May 2011 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=22 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930144021/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/22/sherlock-wins-best-drama-award-baftas |archive-date=30 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Home release and merchandise ==\n\n===DVD and Blu-ray release===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Series\n! colspan=\"3\" | DVD/Blu-ray release dates\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Additional features\n|-\n! Region 1/A\n! Region 2/B\n! Region 4/B\n|-\n! 1\n| 9 November 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-1-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004132HZS/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215204914/https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Season-1-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B004132HZS |archive-date=15 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 30 August 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-1-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B003TO5414/ |work=Amazon |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111175754/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sherlock-1-DVD-Benedict-Cumberbatch/dp/B003TO5414 |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 4 November 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock: Series 1 |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-1/277108/ |work=JB Hi-fi |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923123855/https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-drama/sherlock-series-1/277108/ |archive-date=23 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Audio commentaries \"A Study in Pink\" and \"The Great Game\"\n* \"Unlocking Sherlock\" documentary<ref>{{cite web |title=Unlocking Sherlock |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV271627 |work=BBFC |date=2 August 2010 |accessdate=5 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119205846/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV271627 |archive-date=19 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Original pilot version of \"A Study in Pink\"<ref>''Sherlock'' DVD, Catalogue number: BBCDVD3223</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sherlock DVD review |first=Stu |last=Anderson |wor