{"title_page": "Eric Butcher", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]] and selected by writer/curator, David Dibosa; director of [[Tate Liverpool]], Helen Legg (then director of [[Spike Island Artspace]]); and [[Michael Simpson (painter)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref>, at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\nShortly after the death of his father, Butcher created a series of works from gunpowder residue and clay on burnt paper. These found 'drawings' on paper were from 'spent fireworks cartridges from a beach display [that] had been casually tossed into the sea'<ref name=richnessrightness>(2019).\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\" Carey-Kent, Paul, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>. 'Eric started to gather them up for more suitable disposal. Then he became interested in how the spent energy had left its marks, especially as those traces were \u2013 in line with the aims of his wider practice \u2013 free from the subjectivity of creative decision making'.<ref name=richnessrightness /> \n\nIt is also apparent that the artist is re-evaluating his own resources in his use of paper, taking environmental concerns into the work itself. As he says in his recent Time Trial catalogue, '[in] trying to consume less, tread more lightly on the planet, it would be curiously contradictory not to impose the same logic of questioning on my work. Aluminium production is an energy intensive business, so I am increasingly using recycled and reused materials'.<ref>\"Time Trial\", Butcher, Eric, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]] and selected by writer/curator, David Dibosa; director of [[Tate Liverpool]], Helen Legg (then director of [[Spike Island Artspace]]); and [[Michael Simpson (painter)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref>, at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\nShortly after the death of his father, Butcher created a series of works from gunpowder residue and clay on burnt paper. These found 'drawings' on paper were from 'spent fireworks cartridges from a beach display [that] had been casually tossed into the sea'<ref> name=richnessrightness />\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\" Carey-Kent, Paul, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>. 'Eric started to gather them up for more suitable disposal. Then he became interested in how the spent energy had left its marks, especially as those traces were \u2013 in line with the aims of his wider practice \u2013 free from the subjectivity of creative decision making'.<ref name=richnessrightness /> \n\nIt is also apparent that the artist is re-evaluating his own resources in his use of paper, taking environmental concerns into the work itself. As he says in his recent Time Trial catalogue, '[in] trying to consume less, tread more lightly on the planet, it would be curiously contradictory not to impose the same logic of questioning on my work. Aluminium production is an energy intensive business, so I am increasingly using recycled and reused materials'.<ref>\"Time Trial\", Butcher, Eric, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "name_user": "Barrettjonathan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Butcher"}
{"title_page": "Proto-Romance Language", "text_new": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Dardel & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|k\u0254\u0301rnu\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|k\u0254\u0301rnas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |horn\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute ====\nBroadly speaking, these decline as nouns do.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 32, 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n|pej\u00f3res\n|m\u00e1jor\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|pej\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3res\n|maj\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|pej\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00fa\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative ====\nThis could also connote the near future.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u025b\u0301t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles ====\nOf these there were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain \u27e8saeculum\u27e9 was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce \u27e8knight\u27e9 as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as \u27e8viridiarium\u27e9 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] completely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later at the [[Council of Tours]] to order sermons to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in plain roman speech', i.e. in Romance.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=|pages=295|doi=10.1515/9783110313482|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/963581913|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom) 2|date=2016|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2016|isbn=3-11-045361-4|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|location=|pages=|oclc=963581913|editor-last2=Gouvert|editor-first2=Xavier}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Loporcaro|first=Michele|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1107082342|title=Vowel Length From Latin to Romance|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-965655-4|location=|pages=25-30|oclc=1107082342}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Dworkin|first=Steven N.|date=2016-01-01|title=Do Romanists need to reconstruct Proto-Romance?|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=132|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|issn=1865-9063|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Thaddeus|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110806960|title=A History of the Romance Vowel Systems through Paradigmatic Reconstruction|date=1976-01-31|publisher=De Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-080696-0|location=Berlin, Boston|pages=78}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wilkinson, Hugh E.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1055897845|title=Notes on the development of -KJ-, -TJ- in Spanish and Portuguese|date=1926|publisher=Aoyama Gakuin University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11-14|oclc=1055897845}}\n* {{Citation|last=Zampaulo|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance languages|date=2019-08-22|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780198807384.003.0006|work=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance Languages|volume=|pages=150\u2013199|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-880738-4|access-date=2020-04-01}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=R.|last2=Gaeng|first2=P. A.|date=1992|title=La Declinaison Nominale du Latin Non Classique: Essai d'une Methode de Synthese|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|journal=Probus|volume=4|issue=2|pages=|doi=10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|issn=0921-4771|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert Anderson, 1911-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/422266905|title=Proto-Romance phonology|date=1976|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0-444-00183-2|oclc=422266905}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert A. (Robert Anderson), 1911-1997.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/10773070|title=Proto-Romance Morphology|date=1983|publisher=John Benjamins Pub. Co|year=|isbn=90-272-3522-8|location=|pages=|oclc=10773070}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=Robert|last2=W\u00fcest|first2=Jakob|date=1993|title=Les syst\u00e8mes casuels du prototoman|url=https://elibrary.narr.digital/article/99.125005/vox199310025|journal=Vox Romanica|volume=52|issue=1|pages=25-65|issn=0042-899X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n", "text_old": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Dardel & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|k\u0254\u0301rnu\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|k\u0254\u0301rnas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |horn\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute ====\nBroadly speaking, these decline as nouns do.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 32, 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n|pej\u00f3res\n|m\u00e1jor\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|pej\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3res\n|maj\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|pej\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00fa\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative ====\nThis could also connote the near future.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u025b\u0301t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles ====\nOf these there were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain \u27e8saeculum\u27e9 was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce \u27e8knight\u27e9 as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as \u27e8viridiarium\u27e9 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] completely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later at the [[Council of Tours]] to order sermons to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in plain roman speech' i.e. in Romance.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=|pages=295|doi=10.1515/9783110313482|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/963581913|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom) 2|date=2016|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2016|isbn=3-11-045361-4|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|location=|pages=|oclc=963581913|editor-last2=Gouvert|editor-first2=Xavier}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Loporcaro|first=Michele|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1107082342|title=Vowel Length From Latin to Romance|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-965655-4|location=|pages=25-30|oclc=1107082342}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Dworkin|first=Steven N.|date=2016-01-01|title=Do Romanists need to reconstruct Proto-Romance?|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=132|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|issn=1865-9063|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Thaddeus|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110806960|title=A History of the Romance Vowel Systems through Paradigmatic Reconstruction|date=1976-01-31|publisher=De Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-080696-0|location=Berlin, Boston|pages=78}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wilkinson, Hugh E.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1055897845|title=Notes on the development of -KJ-, -TJ- in Spanish and Portuguese|date=1926|publisher=Aoyama Gakuin University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11-14|oclc=1055897845}}\n* {{Citation|last=Zampaulo|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance languages|date=2019-08-22|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780198807384.003.0006|work=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance Languages|volume=|pages=150\u2013199|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-880738-4|access-date=2020-04-01}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=R.|last2=Gaeng|first2=P. A.|date=1992|title=La Declinaison Nominale du Latin Non Classique: Essai d'une Methode de Synthese|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|journal=Probus|volume=4|issue=2|pages=|doi=10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|issn=0921-4771|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert Anderson, 1911-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/422266905|title=Proto-Romance phonology|date=1976|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0-444-00183-2|oclc=422266905}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert A. (Robert Anderson), 1911-1997.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/10773070|title=Proto-Romance Morphology|date=1983|publisher=John Benjamins Pub. Co|year=|isbn=90-272-3522-8|location=|pages=|oclc=10773070}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=Robert|last2=W\u00fcest|first2=Jakob|date=1993|title=Les syst\u00e8mes casuels du prototoman|url=https://elibrary.narr.digital/article/99.125005/vox199310025|journal=Vox Romanica|volume=52|issue=1|pages=25-65|issn=0042-899X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n", "name_user": "Excelsius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Romance_Language"}
