{"title_page": "Pablo Elisii", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine judoka}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Pablo Elisii\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[Judo]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|10|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Pablo Elisii''' (born 14 October 1971) is an Argentine [[judo]]ka. He competed in the [[Judo at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 86 kg|men's middleweight event]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/el/pablo-elisii-1.html |title=Pablo Elisii Olympic Results |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elisii, Pablo}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male judoka]]\n[[Category:Olympic judoka of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Judoka at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in judo]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Argentina]]\n[[Category:Judoka at the 1995 Pan American Games]]\n{{Argentina-judo-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine judoka}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Pablo Elisii\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[Judo]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|10|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Pablo Elisii''' (born 14 October 1971) is an Argentine [[judo]]ka. He competed in the [[Judo at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 86 kg|men's middleweight event]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/el/pablo-elisii-1.html |title=Pablo Elisii Olympic Results |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elisii, Pablo}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male judoka]]\n[[Category:Olympic judoka of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Judoka at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in judo]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Argentina]]\n[[Category:Judoka at the 1995 Pan American Games]]\n{{Argentina-judo-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pablo_Elisii"}
{"title_page": "Elena Ferrante", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n|name         = Elena Ferrante<br>(pseudonym)\n|image        =\n|image_size   =\n|caption      =\n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|occupation   = Novelist\n|genre        = [[Literary fiction]]\n|notableworks = ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]''\n|years_active = 1992\u2013present\n|nationality  = Italian\n|language     = Italian\n|website      = {{URL|elenaferrante.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Ferrante''' ({{IPA-it|\u02cc\u025b\u02d0lena fer\u02c8rante}}) is a [[pseudonym]]ous Italian [[novelist]]. Ferrante's books, originally published in Italian, have been translated into many languages. Her four-book series of ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]'' are among her best-known works.\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called Ferrante one of the 100 most influential people in 2016.\n\n==Writing==\nElena Ferrante is the name used by the author of half a dozen novels, the best known of which is the four-volume work titled the ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]''.<ref name=\"Donadio\">{{cite news|last1=Donadio|first1=Rahel|title=Who Is Elena Ferrante? An Educated Guess Causes a Stir|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/14/books/who-is-elena-ferrante-an-educated-guess-causes-a-stir.html?_r=0|accessdate=14 March 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=13 March 2016}}</ref><ref>Jenny Turner, \"[http://harpers.org/archive/2014/10/the-secret-sharer-4/2/ The Secret Sharer. Elena Ferrante's existential fiction]\", ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', October 2014.</ref> The ''Neapolitan Novels'' tell the life story of two perceptive and intelligent girls born in [[Naples]] in 1944, who try to create lives for themselves within a violent and stultifying culture. The series consists of ''My Brilliant Friend'' (2012), ''The Story of a New Name'' (2013), ''Those Who Leave And Those Who Stay'' (2014), and ''The Story of the Lost Child'' (2015), which was nominated for the [[Strega Prize]], an Italian literary award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/elena-ferrante-mystery-creator-of-her-neapolitan-novels/story-fnb64oi6-1227269529686 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170126032629/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/the-times/elena-ferrante-mystery-creator-of-her-neapolitan-novels/news-story/e6f2f4d6b1e0fa1756fd5b4a4976b536 |archivedate=2017-01-26 |df= }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-37539258 Elena Ferrante: Journalist defends unmasking 'anonymous' author]</ref>\n\nFerrante holds that \"books, once they are written, have no need of their authors.\"<ref name=\"wood\">{{cite web | url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/01/21/women-on-the-verge | title=Women on the Verge: The Fiction of Elena Ferrante | author=Wood, James | publisher=Newyorker.com | accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> She has repeatedly argued that anonymity is a precondition for her work<ref name=\"argument\" /> and that keeping her true name out of the spotlight is key to her writing process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/10/03/496406869/for-literary-world-unmasking-elena-ferrantes-not-a-scoop-its-a-disgrace For Literary World, Unmasking Elena Ferrante's Not A Scoop. It's A Disgrace]</ref> According to Ferrante, {{quote|Once I knew that the completed book would make its way in the world without me, once I knew that nothing of the concrete, physical me would ever appear beside the volume\u2014as if the book were a little dog and I were its master\u2014it made me see something new about writing. I felt as though I had released the words from myself.<ref name=\"AoF228\" />}}\n\nThe first appearance of her work in English was the publication of a short story entitled \"Delia's Elevator,\" translated by Adria Frizzi in the anthology ''After the War'' (2004).<ref>{{cite book|author=King, Martha|title=After the War: A Collection of Short Fiction by Postwar Italian Women|location=New York|publisher=Italica Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-934977-55-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPNm1NxhvxkC}}</ref> It narrates the movements of the title character on the day of her mother's burial, particularly her return to her safe retreat in the old elevator in the apartment building where she grew up.\n\nThe fourth book of Ferrante's Neapolitan quartet, ''The Story of the Lost Child'', appeared on ''The New York Times''{{'}} 10 Best Books of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 3, 2015|title=The 10 Best Books of 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/02/books/review/best-books-of-2015.html|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Anonymity==\nDespite being recognized as a novelist on an international scale,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-ideal-marriage-according-to-novels |title=The Ideal Marriage, According to Novels |first=Adelle |last=Waldman |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=15 January 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Ferrante has kept her identity secret since the publication of her first novel in 1992.<ref name=\"AoF228\">{{cite news |last1 =Ferri |first1=Sandro |last2=Ferri |first2=Sandra |title=Interview: Elena Ferrante, Art of Fiction No. 228 |url =http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/6370/art-of-fiction-no-228-elena-ferrante |accessdate=13 June 2015| issue=212 |publisher=[[The Paris Review]] |date=Spring 2015}}</ref> Speculation as to her true identity has been rife, and several theories, based on information Ferrante has given in interviews as well as analysis drawn from the content of her novels, have been put forth.\n\nIn 2003, Ferrante published ''[[La Frantumaglia]]'', a volume of letters, essays, reflections and interviews, translated into English in 2016, which sheds some light on her background. In a 2013 article for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', critic [[James Wood (critic)|James Wood]] summarized what is generally accepted about Ferrante, based in part on letters collected in that volume:\n\n{{quote|text=... a number of her letters have been collected and published. From them, we learn that she grew up in [[Naples]], and has lived for periods outside Italy. She has a classics degree; she has referred to being a mother. One could also infer from her fiction and from her interviews that she is not now married...In addition to writing, \"I study, I translate, I teach.\"<ref name=\"wood\" />}}\n\nIn March 2016, Marco Santagata, an Italian novelist and [[philology|philologist]], a scholar of [[Petrarch]] and [[Dante]], and a professor at the [[University of Pisa]],<ref>http://unimap.unipi.it/cercapersone/dettaglio.php?ri=5768&template=dettaglio.tpl</ref> published a paper detailing his theory of Ferrante's identity. Santagata's paper drew on philological analysis of Ferrante's writing, close study of the details about the cityscape of [[Pisa]] described in the novel, and the fact that the author reveals an expert knowledge of modern [[Italian politics]]. Based on this information, he concluded that the author had lived in Pisa but left by 1966, and therefore identified the probable author as Neapolitan professor Marcella Marmo, who studied in Pisa from 1964 to 1966. Both Marmo and the publisher deny Santagata's identification.<ref name=\"Donadio\" />\n\nIn October 2016, investigative reporter [[Claudio Gatti]] published an article jointly in ''[[Il Sole 24 Ore]]'' and ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'', that relied on financial records related to real estate transactions and [[royalties]] payments to draw the conclusion that {{ill|Anita Raja|de}}, a [[Rome]]-based [[translator]], is the real author behind the Ferrante pseudonym.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2016/10/02/elena-ferrante-an-answer/ |title=Elena Ferrante: An Answer? |first=Claudio |last=Gatti |publisher=[[New York Review of Books]] |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Gatti's article was criticized by many in the literary world as a violation of privacy,<ref name=\"argument\">{{cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/minutes/137377/nyrbs-argument-doxing-elena-ferrante-not-good |title=The NYRB's argument for doxing Elena Ferrante is not very good |work=[[The New Republic]] |first=Alex |last=Shepherd |date=2 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"backlash\">{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/backlash-reporter-outs-id-anonymous-writer-behind-elena-111500055.html |title=Backlash for Reporter Who 'Outs' ID of Anonymous Writer Behind Elena Ferrante |work=[[Sky News]]  |publisher=Yahoo! Lifestyle |author=Staff writers |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC 5 October 2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-37556183 |title= Why is the exposure of Elena Ferrante causing such outrage?|last= Alexander |first= Lucy | date= 5 October 2016 |website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 6 October 2016 }}</ref> though Gatti contends that \"by announcing that she would lie on occasion, Ferrante has in a way relinquished her right to disappear behind her books and let them live and grow while their author remained unknown. Indeed, she and her publisher seemed to have fed public interest in her true identity.\"<ref name=\"argument\"/> British novelist [[Matt Haig]] [[Twitter|tweet]]ed, \"Think the pursuit to discover the 'real' Elena Ferrante is a disgrace and also pointless. A writer's truest self is the books they write.\"<ref name=\"backlash\" /> The writer [[Jeanette Winterson]] denounced Gatti's investigations as malicious and sexist:\n\n{{quote|at the bottom of this so-called investigation into Ferrante's identity is an obsessional outrage at the success of a writer \u2013 female \u2013 who decided to write, publish and promote her books on her own terms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/oct/07/unmasking-elena-ferrante|title=The malice and sexism behind the 'unmasking' of Elena Ferrante|last=Winterson|first=Jeanette|date=2016-10-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>}}\n\nOthers, however, have suggested that knowledge of Ferrante's biography is indeed relevant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/elenic-question/|title=The Elenic Question|last1=Emre|first1=Merve |last2=Gutkin |first2=Len|date=6 October 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/oct/08/prissy-response-to-elena-ferrante-being-unmasked|title=Why the prissy reaction to Ferrante being unmasked?|last=Bennett|first=Catherine|date=8 October 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> According to Winterson, the desire to uncover Ferrante's identity constitutes an act of sexism in itself, based on the assumption that Gatti comes from a Catholic country with deep patriarchal roots. Indeed, the Winterson piece published by the ''Guardian'' says nothing else about Gatti.\n\nIn December 2016, the controversial Italian prankster<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/web-culture/meet-the-internets-greatest-liar-tommaso-debenedetti-whose-hoaxes-have-fooled-millions-20160629-gpuzzs.html |title=Meet the internet's 'greatest liar' Tommaso Debenedetti, whose hoaxes have fooled millions |first=Caitlin |last=Dewey |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> [[Tommaso Debenedetti]] published on the website of the Spanish daily ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' a purported interview with Raja confirming she is Elena Ferrante; this was quickly denied by Ferrante's publisher, who called the interview a fake.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lanotiziagiornale.it/anita-raja-elena-ferrante-fake/ |title=Anita Raja conferma su Twitter: 'sono io Elena Ferrante. Ma ora lasciatemi vivere (e scrivere) in pace'. Ma dalla casa editrice smentiscono: 'tutto falso, \u00e8 un fake' |author=Staff writers |work=[[LaNotizia]] |date=5 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, a team of scholars, computer scientists, philologists and linguists at the [[University of Padua]] analyzed 150 novels written in Italian by 40 different authors, including seven books by Elena Ferrante, but none by Raja. Based on analysis using several authorship attribution models, they concluded that Anita Raja's husband, author and journalist [[Domenico Starnone]], is the probable author of the Ferrante novels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320131096_Elena_Ferrante_Unmasked |title=Elena Ferrante Unmasked |first=Jacques |last=Savoy |work=[[Universit\u00e9 de Neuch\u00e2tel]] |publisher=[[ResearchGate]] |date=September 2017 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Raja has worked for E/O Publishing as copy editor and has been editing Starnone's books for years.\n\nFerrante has repeatedly dismissed suggestions that she is actually a man, telling ''Vanity Fair'' in 2015 that questions about her gender are rooted in a presumed \"weakness\" of female writers.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/08/elena-ferrante-interview-the-story-of-the-lost-child |title=The Mysterious, Anonymous Author Elena Ferrante on the Conclusion of Her Neapolitan Novels |last=Schappell |first=Elissa |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=27 August 2015 |access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nTwo of Ferrante's novels have been turned into films. ''Troubling Love'' (''L'amore molesto'') became the feature film ''[[Nasty Love]]'' directed by [[Mario Martone]], while ''The Days of Abandonment'' (''I giorni dell'abbandono'') became [[I giorni dell'abbandono|a film of the same title]] directed by [[Roberto Faenza]]. In her nonfiction book ''Fragments'' (''La frantumaglia'' 2003), Ferrante speaks of her experiences as a writer.\n\nIn 2016, it was reported that a 32-part television series, ''The Neapolitan Novels'', was in the works, co-produced by the Italian producer Wildside for Fandango Productions, with screenwriting led by the writer Francesco Piccolo.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moylan |first1=Brian |title=Elena Ferrante\u2019s Neapolitan novels set for TV adaptation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2016/feb/09/neopolitan-novels-elena-ferrante-tv-adaptation |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 February 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, the first two episodes of the renamed ''[[My Brilliant Friend (miniseries)|My Brilliant Friend]]'', an Italian-language [[miniseries]] co-produced by American premium cable network [[HBO]] and Italian networks [[RAI]] and [[TIMvision]],<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite news |url=https://medium.com/hbo-cinemax-pr/my-brilliant-friend-debuts-sunday-nov-18-on-hbo-d335239ce9d7 |title=My Brilliant Friend Debuts Sunday, Nov. 18 on HBO |publisher=[[HBO]] |date=13 September 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> were aired at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=Miniseries>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/my-brilliant-friend-hbo-1202921018/ |title=TV Review: \u2018My Brilliant Friend\u2019 on HBO |first=Daniel |last=D'Addario |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2 September 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> HBO started airing the complete eight episode miniseries, focusing on the first book in ''The Neapolitan Novels'', in November 2018.<ref name=\"announce\"/>\n\n==Works==\n{{See also|Neapolitan Novels}}\n* ''L'amore molesto'' (1992; English translation: ''Troubling Love'', 2006); filmed as ''[[Nasty Love]]'' (1995)\n* ''I giorni dell'abbandono'' (2002; English translation: ''[[The Days of Abandonment]]'', 2005)\n* ''La frantumaglia'' (2003; English translation ''Fragments'', 2016)\n* ''La figlia oscura'' (2006; English translation: ''The Lost Daughter'', 2008)\n* ''La spiaggia di notte'' (2007; English translation: ''The Beach at Night'', 2016)\n* ''L'amica geniale'' (2011; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|My Brilliant Friend]]'', 2012). {{OCLC|778419313}}. \n* ''Storia del nuovo cognome'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 2 (2012; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|The Story of a New Name]]'', 2013). {{OCLC|829451619}}. \n* ''Storia di chi fugge e di chi resta'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 3 (2013; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|Those Who Leave and Those Who Stay]]'', 2014). {{OCLC|870919836}}. \n* ''Storia della bambina perduta'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 4 (2014; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|The Story of the Lost Child]]'', 2015). {{OCLC|910239891}}.\n* ''La vita bugiarda degli adulti'' (2019). {{OCLC|1126993616}}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*2016 [[Time 100#2016|TIME 100 Most Influential People]]<ref name=\"TIME100\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4299844/elena-ferrante-2016-time-100/ |title= TIME 100 Artists, Elena Ferrante |publisher=Time |author=Lauren Groff |date=April 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Man Booker International Prize]], shortlisted for ''The Story of the Lost Child''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35771674|title='Anonymous' author on international Man Booker longlist|date=10 March 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/books/features/Elena-Ferrante-could-be-the-first-ever-anonymous-Booker-winner/articleshow/51837635.cms?|title=Elena Ferrante could be the first-ever anonymous Booker winner - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Independent Publisher Book Awards|Independent Publisher Book Award]] - Gold Medal (literary fiction), for ''The Story of the Lost Child''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=2045 |title=2016 Independent Publisher Book Awards Results |date= |website=Independent Publisher |accessdate=10 May 2016}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Best Translated Book Award]], shortlisted for ''The Story of a New Name'', translated from the Italian by [[Ann Goldstein (translator)|Ann Goldstein]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?id=10722 |title=2014 Best Translated Book Awards: Fiction Finalists |publisher=Three Percent |author=Chad W. Post |date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===General references===\n* \"Anita Raja a Tommaso Debenedetti: Yo Soy Elena Ferrante\" on ''El Mundo'', Madrid 10-12-2016\n\n===Inline citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tiziana de Rogatis, Elena Ferrante. Parole chiave, e/o, Roma 2018\n* Tiziana de Rogatis, Elena Ferrante's Key Words, Europa Editions, New York 2019\n* Buonanno, Elda. ''La Frantumaglia: Elena Ferrante's \"fragmented self\"'', PhD thesis, [[City University of New York]], 2011.\n* Milkova, Stiliana. \"Mothers, Daughters, Dolls: On Disgust in Elena Ferrante's ''La figlia oscura''\", ''Italian Culture'' 31:2 (September 2013).\n* Mullenneaux, Lisa. \"Naples' Little Women: The Fiction of Elena Ferrante,\" Penington Press, 2016.\n* {{cite journal |last=Sharma |first=Bhasha Shukla |title=Doll, daughter, (m)other: switching roles in Elena Ferrante's ''The Lost Daughter'' |journal=Lapiz Lazuli: An International Literary Journal |volume=8 |issue=1 |year=2018 |pages=46\u201354 |url=http://pintersociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/5-Bhasha-Shukla-Sharma.pdf }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://elenaferrante.com Official website]\n* [http://www.iowareview.org/blog/elena-ferrantes-troubling-love Elena Ferrante's ''Troubling Love''] \u2013 book review in the ''[[Iowa Review]]''\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/oct/31/elena-ferrante-literary-sensation-nobody-knows Elena Ferrante: the global literary sensation nobody knows] \u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/knausgaard-or-ferrante Knausgaard or Ferrante] - ''[[The New Yorker]]''\n\n{{Portal bar|Italy|Biography|Literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferrante, Elena}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian novelists]]\n[[Category:People from Naples]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous women writers]]\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:Italian women novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n|name         = Elena Ferrante<br>(pseudonym)\n|image        =\n|image_size   =\n|caption      =\n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|occupation   = Novelist\n|genre        = [[Literary fiction]]\n|notableworks = ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]''\n|years_active = 1992\u2013present\n|nationality  = Italian\n|language     = Italian\n|website      = {{URL|elenaferrante.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Ferrante''' ({{IPA-it|\u02cc\u025b\u02d0lena fer\u02c8rante}}) is a [[pseudonym]]ous Italian [[novelist]]. Ferrante's books, originally published in Italian, have been translated into many languages. Her four-book series of ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]'' are among her best-known works.\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called Ferrante one of the 100 most influential people in 2016.\n\n==Writing==\nElena Ferrante is the name used by the author of half a dozen novels, the best known of which is the four-volume work entitled the ''[[Neapolitan Novels]]''.<ref name=\"Donadio\">{{cite news|last1=Donadio|first1=Rahel|title=Who Is Elena Ferrante? An Educated Guess Causes a Stir|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/14/books/who-is-elena-ferrante-an-educated-guess-causes-a-stir.html?_r=0|accessdate=14 March 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=13 March 2016}}</ref><ref>Jenny Turner, \"[http://harpers.org/archive/2014/10/the-secret-sharer-4/2/ The Secret Sharer. Elena Ferrante's existential fiction]\", ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', October 2014.</ref> The ''Neapolitan Novels'' tell the life story of two perceptive and intelligent girls born in [[Naples]] in 1944, who try to create lives for themselves within a violent and stultifying culture. The series consists of ''My Brilliant Friend'' (2012), ''The Story of a New Name'' (2013), ''Those Who Leave And Those Who Stay'' (2014), and ''The Story of the Lost Child'' (2015), which was nominated for the [[Strega Prize]], an Italian literary award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/elena-ferrante-mystery-creator-of-her-neapolitan-novels/story-fnb64oi6-1227269529686 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170126032629/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/the-times/elena-ferrante-mystery-creator-of-her-neapolitan-novels/news-story/e6f2f4d6b1e0fa1756fd5b4a4976b536 |archivedate=2017-01-26 |df= }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-37539258 Elena Ferrante: Journalist defends unmasking 'anonymous' author]</ref>\n\nFerrante holds that \"books, once they are written, have no need of their authors.\"<ref name=\"wood\">{{cite web | url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/01/21/women-on-the-verge | title=Women on the Verge: The Fiction of Elena Ferrante | author=Wood, James | publisher=Newyorker.com | accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> She has repeatedly argued that anonymity is a precondition for her work<ref name=\"argument\" /> and that keeping her true name out of the spotlight is key to her writing process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/10/03/496406869/for-literary-world-unmasking-elena-ferrantes-not-a-scoop-its-a-disgrace For Literary World, Unmasking Elena Ferrante's Not A Scoop. It's A Disgrace]</ref> According to Ferrante, {{quote|Once I knew that the completed book would make its way in the world without me, once I knew that nothing of the concrete, physical me would ever appear beside the volume\u2014as if the book were a little dog and I were its master\u2014it made me see something new about writing. I felt as though I had released the words from myself.<ref name=\"AoF228\" />}}\n\nThe first appearance of her work in English was the publication of a short story entitled \"Delia's Elevator,\" translated by Adria Frizzi in the anthology ''After the War'' (2004).<ref>{{cite book|author=King, Martha|title=After the War: A Collection of Short Fiction by Postwar Italian Women|location=New York|publisher=Italica Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-934977-55-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPNm1NxhvxkC}}</ref> It narrates the movements of the title character on the day of her mother's burial, particularly her return to her safe retreat in the old elevator in the apartment building where she grew up.\n\nThe fourth book of Ferrante's Neapolitan quartet, ''The Story of the Lost Child'', appeared on ''The New York Times''{{'}} 10 Best Books of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 3, 2015|title=The 10 Best Books of 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/02/books/review/best-books-of-2015.html|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Anonymity==\nDespite being recognized as a novelist on an international scale,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-ideal-marriage-according-to-novels |title=The Ideal Marriage, According to Novels |first=Adelle |last=Waldman |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=15 January 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Ferrante has kept her identity secret since the publication of her first novel in 1992.<ref name=\"AoF228\">{{cite news |last1 =Ferri |first1=Sandro |last2=Ferri |first2=Sandra |title=Interview: Elena Ferrante, Art of Fiction No. 228 |url =http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/6370/art-of-fiction-no-228-elena-ferrante |accessdate=13 June 2015| issue=212 |publisher=[[The Paris Review]] |date=Spring 2015}}</ref> Speculation as to her true identity has been rife, and several theories, based on information Ferrante has given in interviews as well as analysis drawn from the content of her novels, have been put forth.\n\nIn 2003, Ferrante published ''[[La Frantumaglia]]'', a volume of letters, essays, reflections and interviews, translated into English in 2016, which sheds some light on her background. In a 2013 article for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', critic [[James Wood (critic)|James Wood]] summarized what is generally accepted about Ferrante, based in part on letters collected in that volume:\n\n{{quote|text=... a number of her letters have been collected and published. From them, we learn that she grew up in [[Naples]], and has lived for periods outside Italy. She has a classics degree; she has referred to being a mother. One could also infer from her fiction and from her interviews that she is not now married...In addition to writing, \"I study, I translate, I teach.\"<ref name=\"wood\" />}}\n\nIn March 2016, Marco Santagata, an Italian novelist and [[philology|philologist]], a scholar of [[Petrarch]] and [[Dante]], and a professor at the [[University of Pisa]],<ref>http://unimap.unipi.it/cercapersone/dettaglio.php?ri=5768&template=dettaglio.tpl</ref> published a paper detailing his theory of Ferrante's identity. Santagata's paper drew on philological analysis of Ferrante's writing, close study of the details about the cityscape of [[Pisa]] described in the novel, and the fact that the author reveals an expert knowledge of modern [[Italian politics]]. Based on this information, he concluded that the author had lived in Pisa but left by 1966, and therefore identified the probable author as Neapolitan professor Marcella Marmo, who studied in Pisa from 1964 to 1966. Both Marmo and the publisher deny Santagata's identification.<ref name=\"Donadio\" />\n\nIn October 2016, investigative reporter [[Claudio Gatti]] published an article jointly in ''[[Il Sole 24 Ore]]'' and ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'', that relied on financial records related to real estate transactions and [[royalties]] payments to draw the conclusion that {{ill|Anita Raja|de}}, a [[Rome]]-based [[translator]], is the real author behind the Ferrante pseudonym.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2016/10/02/elena-ferrante-an-answer/ |title=Elena Ferrante: An Answer? |first=Claudio |last=Gatti |publisher=[[New York Review of Books]] |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Gatti's article was criticized by many in the literary world as a violation of privacy,<ref name=\"argument\">{{cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/minutes/137377/nyrbs-argument-doxing-elena-ferrante-not-good |title=The NYRB's argument for doxing Elena Ferrante is not very good |work=[[The New Republic]] |first=Alex |last=Shepherd |date=2 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"backlash\">{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/backlash-reporter-outs-id-anonymous-writer-behind-elena-111500055.html |title=Backlash for Reporter Who 'Outs' ID of Anonymous Writer Behind Elena Ferrante |work=[[Sky News]]  |publisher=Yahoo! Lifestyle |author=Staff writers |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC 5 October 2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-37556183 |title= Why is the exposure of Elena Ferrante causing such outrage?|last= Alexander |first= Lucy | date= 5 October 2016 |website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 6 October 2016 }}</ref> though Gatti contends that \"by announcing that she would lie on occasion, Ferrante has in a way relinquished her right to disappear behind her books and let them live and grow while their author remained unknown. Indeed, she and her publisher seemed to have fed public interest in her true identity.\"<ref name=\"argument\"/> British novelist [[Matt Haig]] [[Twitter|tweet]]ed, \"Think the pursuit to discover the 'real' Elena Ferrante is a disgrace and also pointless. A writer's truest self is the books they write.\"<ref name=\"backlash\" /> The writer [[Jeanette Winterson]] denounced Gatti's investigations as malicious and sexist:\n\n{{quote|at the bottom of this so-called investigation into Ferrante's identity is an obsessional outrage at the success of a writer \u2013 female \u2013 who decided to write, publish and promote her books on her own terms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/oct/07/unmasking-elena-ferrante|title=The malice and sexism behind the 'unmasking' of Elena Ferrante|last=Winterson|first=Jeanette|date=2016-10-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>}}\n\nOthers, however, have suggested that knowledge of Ferrante's biography is indeed relevant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/elenic-question/|title=The Elenic Question|last1=Emre|first1=Merve |last2=Gutkin |first2=Len|date=6 October 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/oct/08/prissy-response-to-elena-ferrante-being-unmasked|title=Why the prissy reaction to Ferrante being unmasked?|last=Bennett|first=Catherine|date=8 October 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> According to Winterson, the desire to uncover Ferrante's identity constitutes an act of sexism in itself, based on the assumption that Gatti comes from a Catholic country with deep patriarchal roots. Indeed, the Winterson piece published by the ''Guardian'' says nothing else about Gatti.\n\nIn December 2016, the controversial Italian prankster<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/web-culture/meet-the-internets-greatest-liar-tommaso-debenedetti-whose-hoaxes-have-fooled-millions-20160629-gpuzzs.html |title=Meet the internet's 'greatest liar' Tommaso Debenedetti, whose hoaxes have fooled millions |first=Caitlin |last=Dewey |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> [[Tommaso Debenedetti]] published on the website of the Spanish daily ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' a purported interview with Raja confirming she is Elena Ferrante; this was quickly denied by Ferrante's publisher, who called the interview a fake.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lanotiziagiornale.it/anita-raja-elena-ferrante-fake/ |title=Anita Raja conferma su Twitter: 'sono io Elena Ferrante. Ma ora lasciatemi vivere (e scrivere) in pace'. Ma dalla casa editrice smentiscono: 'tutto falso, \u00e8 un fake' |author=Staff writers |work=[[LaNotizia]] |date=5 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, a team of scholars, computer scientists, philologists and linguists at the [[University of Padua]] analyzed 150 novels written in Italian by 40 different authors, including seven books by Elena Ferrante, but none by Raja. Based on analysis using several authorship attribution models, they concluded that Anita Raja's husband, author and journalist [[Domenico Starnone]], is the probable author of the Ferrante novels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320131096_Elena_Ferrante_Unmasked |title=Elena Ferrante Unmasked |first=Jacques |last=Savoy |work=[[Universit\u00e9 de Neuch\u00e2tel]] |publisher=[[ResearchGate]] |date=September 2017 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> Raja has worked for E/O Publishing as copy editor and has been editing Starnone's books for years.\n\nFerrante has repeatedly dismissed suggestions that she is actually a man, telling ''Vanity Fair'' in 2015 that questions about her gender are rooted in a presumed \"weakness\" of female writers.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/08/elena-ferrante-interview-the-story-of-the-lost-child |title=The Mysterious, Anonymous Author Elena Ferrante on the Conclusion of Her Neapolitan Novels |last=Schappell |first=Elissa |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=27 August 2015 |access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nTwo of Ferrante's novels have been turned into films. ''Troubling Love'' (''L'amore molesto'') became the feature film ''[[Nasty Love]]'' directed by [[Mario Martone]], while ''The Days of Abandonment'' (''I giorni dell'abbandono'') became [[I giorni dell'abbandono|a film of the same title]] directed by [[Roberto Faenza]]. In her nonfiction book ''Fragments'' (''La frantumaglia'' 2003), Ferrante speaks of her experiences as a writer.\n\nIn 2016, it was reported that a 32-part television series, ''The Neapolitan Novels'', was in the works, co-produced by the Italian producer Wildside for Fandango Productions, with screenwriting led by the writer Francesco Piccolo.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moylan |first1=Brian |title=Elena Ferrante\u2019s Neapolitan novels set for TV adaptation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2016/feb/09/neopolitan-novels-elena-ferrante-tv-adaptation |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 February 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, the first two episodes of the renamed ''[[My Brilliant Friend (miniseries)|My Brilliant Friend]]'', an Italian-language [[miniseries]] co-produced by American premium cable network [[HBO]] and Italian networks [[RAI]] and [[TIMvision]],<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite news |url=https://medium.com/hbo-cinemax-pr/my-brilliant-friend-debuts-sunday-nov-18-on-hbo-d335239ce9d7 |title=My Brilliant Friend Debuts Sunday, Nov. 18 on HBO |publisher=[[HBO]] |date=13 September 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> were aired at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=Miniseries>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/my-brilliant-friend-hbo-1202921018/ |title=TV Review: \u2018My Brilliant Friend\u2019 on HBO |first=Daniel |last=D'Addario |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2 September 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> HBO started airing the complete eight episode miniseries, focusing on the first book in ''The Neapolitan Novels'', in November 2018.<ref name=\"announce\"/>\n\n==Works==\n{{See also|Neapolitan Novels}}\n* ''L'amore molesto'' (1992; English translation: ''Troubling Love'', 2006); filmed as ''[[Nasty Love]]'' (1995)\n* ''I giorni dell'abbandono'' (2002; English translation: ''[[The Days of Abandonment]]'', 2005)\n* ''La frantumaglia'' (2003; English translation ''Fragments'', 2016)\n* ''La figlia oscura'' (2006; English translation: ''The Lost Daughter'', 2008)\n* ''La spiaggia di notte'' (2007; English translation: ''The Beach at Night'', 2016)\n* ''L'amica geniale'' (2011; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|My Brilliant Friend]]'', 2012). {{OCLC|778419313}}. \n* ''Storia del nuovo cognome'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 2 (2012; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|The Story of a New Name]]'', 2013). {{OCLC|829451619}}. \n* ''Storia di chi fugge e di chi resta'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 3 (2013; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|Those Who Leave and Those Who Stay]]'', 2014). {{OCLC|870919836}}. \n* ''Storia della bambina perduta'', ''L'amica geniale'' volume 4 (2014; English translation: ''[[Neapolitan Novels|The Story of the Lost Child]]'', 2015). {{OCLC|910239891}}.\n* ''La vita bugiarda degli adulti'' (2019). {{OCLC|1126993616}}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*2016 [[Time 100#2016|TIME 100 Most Influential People]]<ref name=\"TIME100\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4299844/elena-ferrante-2016-time-100/ |title= TIME 100 Artists, Elena Ferrante |publisher=Time |author=Lauren Groff |date=April 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Man Booker International Prize]], shortlisted for ''The Story of the Lost Child''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35771674|title='Anonymous' author on international Man Booker longlist|date=10 March 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/books/features/Elena-Ferrante-could-be-the-first-ever-anonymous-Booker-winner/articleshow/51837635.cms?|title=Elena Ferrante could be the first-ever anonymous Booker winner - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Independent Publisher Book Awards|Independent Publisher Book Award]] - Gold Medal (literary fiction), for ''The Story of the Lost Child''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=2045 |title=2016 Independent Publisher Book Awards Results |date= |website=Independent Publisher |accessdate=10 May 2016}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Best Translated Book Award]], shortlisted for ''The Story of a New Name'', translated from the Italian by [[Ann Goldstein (translator)|Ann Goldstein]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?id=10722 |title=2014 Best Translated Book Awards: Fiction Finalists |publisher=Three Percent |author=Chad W. Post |date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===General references===\n* \"Anita Raja a Tommaso Debenedetti: Yo Soy Elena Ferrante\" on ''El Mundo'', Madrid 10-12-2016\n\n===Inline citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tiziana de Rogatis, Elena Ferrante. Parole chiave, e/o, Roma 2018\n* Tiziana de Rogatis, Elena Ferrante's Key Words, Europa Editions, New York 2019\n* Buonanno, Elda. ''La Frantumaglia: Elena Ferrante's \"fragmented self\"'', PhD thesis, [[City University of New York]], 2011.\n* Milkova, Stiliana. \"Mothers, Daughters, Dolls: On Disgust in Elena Ferrante's ''La figlia oscura''\", ''Italian Culture'' 31:2 (September 2013).\n* Mullenneaux, Lisa. \"Naples' Little Women: The Fiction of Elena Ferrante,\" Penington Press, 2016.\n* {{cite journal |last=Sharma |first=Bhasha Shukla |title=Doll, daughter, (m)other: switching roles in Elena Ferrante's ''The Lost Daughter'' |journal=Lapiz Lazuli: An International Literary Journal |volume=8 |issue=1 |year=2018 |pages=46\u201354 |url=http://pintersociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/5-Bhasha-Shukla-Sharma.pdf }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://elenaferrante.com Official website]\n* [http://www.iowareview.org/blog/elena-ferrantes-troubling-love Elena Ferrante's ''Troubling Love''] \u2013 book review in the ''[[Iowa Review]]''\n* 